<HTML><HEAD>  <TITLE>Consolidated Interim Report</TITLE>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac"></HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" LINK="#2060a0" VLINK="#606060"ALINK="#e0e0ff"><P ALIGN=CENTER><!--NOEDIT--><center><!--/NOEDIT--><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif" BORDER="0" WIDTH="89" HEIGHT="33" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/newskl.gif"BORDER="0" WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="60919_e.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif" BORDER="0" WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif" BORDER="0" WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"BORDER="0" WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif" BORDER="0" WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR><IMG SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif" WIDTH="592" HEIGHT="16" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Consolidated Interim Report<br>January to September 1996</FONT></B></P><B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>Sales revenue for first nine months 11 % up<br>Continued positive trend in earnings </FONT></B><p><P ALIGN=CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="380"><P><I>Stuttgart, November 7, 1996</I><BR>Daimler-Benz achieved substantially increased sales revenues in all corporate units of the group as well as in the directly-reporting businesses. Sales revenues for January to September 1996 were up 11 % to DM 75.9 billion. As already reported at the end of August, the company expects consolidated earnings for the second half of the year to surpass those of the first half of the year (operating profit January to June 1996: DM 827 mill.).<p>This trend vindicates our course of focusing on high-growth, high-earnings fields of activity, commented Daimler-Benz Chairman J&uuml;rgen E. Schrempp.<p>Summing up the first nine months of 1996, the Daimler-Benz letter to shareholders published today also states that Mercedes-Benz sales revenues increased by 8 % to just under DM 57 billion during this period. Comparably calculated sales revenues of Daimler-Benz Aerospace (Dasa) increased by 18 % to just under DM 8.3 billion. Daimler-Benz InterServices (debis) maintained its dynamic growth, with a 14 % rise in sales to DM 9.8 billion.<p>Revenues also increased during the period under view in the businesses which report directly to Daimler-Benz AG (Rail Systems/Adtranz, Microelectronics/Temic, Diesel Engines/MTU Friedrichshafen, Recognition and Sorting Systems/Electrocom). These businesses posted total sales revenues of DM 5.5 billion.<p>This positive trend in business seems set to continue in the fourth quarter of the year, so that Daimler-Benz expects full-year revenues of over DM 105 billion. It is particularly encouraging to note that the sharp increases mentioned above were achieved despite relatively modest trends in numerous product markets and regions. The Daimler-Benz group registered increased business in virtually all parts of the world.<p>On September 30, 1996, the Daimler-Benz group had 290,031 employees worldwide (comparable figure for 1995: 291,226), of whom 223,106 (September 30, 1995: 226,701) worked in Germany and 66,925 (September 30, 1995: 64,525) elsewhere.<p>The positive trend in performance at Mercedes-Benz is due above all to new, successful products and significant productivity advances. Sales revenues increased during the period to DM 56.9 billion. An above-average increase of 11 % to DM 22.6 billion was recorded in Germany, and strong growth was also recorded in Western Europe outside Germany (+ 18%), the USA (+ 11%) and Japan (+ 21%).<p>Car sales revenues increased by 16 %, while sales of commercial vehicles showed a slight decline. This is attributable to the unfavourable conditions for trucks in Germany and important overseas markets and the model change in the heavy-duty segment. The companys world sales of commercial vehicles increased in unit terms however by 5 % to 248,600 vehicles, largely spurred by van business. <p>The Mercedes-Benz dealer network sold 491,000 cars to customers during the period under review. Consolidated unit sales, which do not take account of reduced stocks in the dealer network,  totalled 481,300 units, 13 % more than in the first nine months of 1995.<p>The largest increases in revenues were achieved by the Propulsion Systems (+ 48 %) and Space Systems (+ 51 %) business units of Daimler-Benz Aerospace (Dasa). Aircraft sales (+ 5%) and sales of the Defence and Civil Systems business unit ( + 3%) on the other hand increased only slightly. Orders received in the first nine months of 1996 were 89 % up on the first nine months of 1995, at DM 13.6 billion. 269 aircraft were ordered from Airbus in the first three quarters of the year, as many as in the previous three years together.<p>Dasa continued to move forward with its competitiveness-improvement measures, thus further reducing the dependence of its results on the value of the dollar.<p>The dynamic expansion in business of Daimler-Benz InterServices (debis) was achieved above all by the Systemhaus (+ 14%), Financial Services (+ 12%) and Mobile Communication Services (+70%) units. The Marketing Services unit was made independent.<p>In Rail Systems, the Daimler-Benz share in the revenues of the joint venture Adtranz was DM 1.9 billion. Orders worth DM 2.1 billion were received for the period from January to September. In October, further large orders were received from China, Singapore, Turkey and Thailand.<p>Sales of Microelectronics from January to September totalled DM 1.8 billion (+ 11%). Orders received fell by 4% to DM 1.7 billion, primarily due to the weakness of the semiconductor market.<p>The Diesel Engines business unit increased its revenues by 13% to DM 1.1 billion. Orders received rose by 14% to DM 1.2 billion, above all in the high-growth segments Distributed Power Supply Systems and Commercial Ships.<p>Recognition and Sorting Systems doubled its sales revenues to DM 700 million, chiefly due to the invoicing of large orders from the US and German Post Offices. Orders received once again exceeded sales revenues.</TD></TR></TABLE></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><BR><IMG SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif" WIDTH="592" HEIGHT="16" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" WIDTH="550"><H5><A HREF="61107_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch&nbsp;]</I> </A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home&nbsp;]</I></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>News&nbsp;]</I> </A><A HREF="60919_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next&nbsp;]</I></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search&nbsp;]</I> </A><AHREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog&nbsp;]</I> </A><A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help&nbsp;]</I></A></H5></TD></TR></TABLE></P><ADDRESS ALIGN=CENTER>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 11/07/1996</ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
