<html>

<head>
<title>Consolidated Interim Report: Mercedes-Benz</title>

</head>

<body background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" text="#000000" link="#2060A0" vlink="#606060" alink="#E0E0FF">
<p align=center><a href="../../index_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/db_home.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=89 height=33></a> <a href="../facts_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/factskl.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=54 height=44></a> <a href="dasa_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/menu_rig.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=54 height=44></a> <a href="../../search/search_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/db_such.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=54 height=44></a> <a href="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/mailkl.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=54 height=44></a> <a href="../../help/help_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/helpkl.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=54 height=44></a> <br>
<img src="../../lines/db_592.gif" align=bottom width=592 height=16></p>
<p align=center><font size=5><b>Mercedes-Benz</b></font> </p>
<div align=center><center>
<table>
<tr><td valign=bottom><font size=2>DM amounts in millions</font> </td><td></td><td align=right valign=bottom width=130><b>01-09/96</b></td><td></td><td align=right width=130><b>01-09/95</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right valign=top width=210></td><td></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=6><hr>
</td></tr>
<tr><td>Revenues </td><td></td><td align=right>56,900</td><td></td><td align=right>52,587</td></tr>
<tr><td>Employees <font size=2>(9/30)</font> </td><td></td><td align=right>198,912</td><td></td><td align=right>202,868</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=6><hr>
</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Passenger Cars</b> </td></tr>
<tr><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>Revenues </td><td></td><td align=right>33,953</td><td></td><td align=right>29,312</td></tr>
<tr><td>Production (units) </td><td></td><td align=right>484,865</td><td></td><td align=right>442,345</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sales (units) </td><td></td><td align=right>481,323</td><td></td><td align=right>426,969</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=6><hr>
</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Commercial Vehicles</b> </td></tr>
<tr><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>Revenues </td><td></td><td align=right>22,947</td><td></td><td align=right>23,275</td></tr>
<tr><td>Production (units) </td><td></td><td align=right>246,084</td><td></td><td align=right>250,452</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sales (units) </td><td></td><td align=right>248,602</td><td></td><td align=right>236,188</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=6><hr>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p></p>
</center></div>
<div align=center><center>
<table>
<tr><td valign=top width=380>Despite the rather restrained development of important 
automotive markets, the positive business trend at 
Mercedes-Benz continued in the third quarter of 1996. The 
expansion was largely the result of successful new products as 
well as a definite boost in productivity and the related 
improvement in the price/value ratio.<p>In total, Mercedes-Benz revenues rose 8% to DM 56.9 
billion. Business volume in Germany was up 11% to DM 22.6 
billion; this represents an above-average increase. But 
Mercedes-Benz also reported vigorous growth in revenues in 
the rest of Western Europe, in the USA, and in Japan. The 
expansion was experienced primarily in the passenger car 
sector, where revenues were up 16%. In commercial vehicles, 
on the other hand, revenues were slightly below the high 
previous year&#146;s level, a drop that is related above all to the 
unfavorable market situation for trucks in Germany and 
important overseas markets and to the model change in the 
heavy-duty trucks class.</p>
<p>In passenger cars, the first nine months of 1996 were 
characterized by the Mercedes-Benz product offensive. The 
T-Models of the C- and E-Class, the SLK roadster, and the 
V-Class minivans were exceptionally well-received by our 
customers. With 481,300 units sold worldwide (including 
off-road vehicles) sales in the passenger car sector were up 
13% compared with the first three quarters of 1995. The 
development was especially encouraging in Germany, where 
sales rose 17% and Mercedes-Benz expanded its market 
share. In foreign markets, a total of nearly 280,000 passenger 
cars were sold, surpassing the all-time record set in 1995 by 
another 10%. In Japan alone, sales advanced by 45%, but 
even in the stagnant US market a 20% increase was reported. 
Mercedes-Benz thus continued to expand its competitive 
position in the markets of the Triad above all.</p>
<p>While sales of the S-Class remained below the level achieved 
a year earlier as a result of the new tax treatment of business 
cars in Germany in particular, the trend in the E-Class was 
exceptionally positive and the C-Class maintained its strong 
market position. Because of the favorable sales situation, 
passenger car production was increased by 10% to almost 
485,000 units.</p>
<p>At 248,600 units, sales of Mercedes-Benz commercial 
vehicles were 5% higher than in the first nine months of the 
previous year, again for the most part thanks to the 
Mercedes-Benz product strategy. For instance, the market 
position in Western Europe was clearly expanded with the 
successful Sprinter and Vito vans. Van sales rose in Western 
Europe outside of Germany above all (up 46%), but also in 
Germany, where an 8% increase was reported in an otherwise 
recessive market. With 105,000 vans sold worldwide, sales in <br>
that sector surpassed the same period in 1995 by 29%. The 
new heavy-duty truck Actros was received favorably by our 
Western European customers, which is also confirmed by the 
development of incoming orders. Because of the difficult 
situation in important markets, however, and because the 
model change in the heavy-duty class was not completed 
before October, truck sales did not reach the level of the 
previous year, most notably in Western Europe. New 
registrations of Mercedes-Benz trucks over 6 tons were up 
5% to 21,700 units in Western Europe outside Germany, 
whereas in Germany the weak market condition was 
responsible for an 11% drop to 23,100 vehicles. EvoBus 
GmbH was able to sell 4,700 complete buses and bus chassis 
of the Mercedes-Benz and Setra makes (up 12%) despite an 
aggressive market in terms of pricing and competition. The 
Unimog business received a significant boost from a large 
order for 540 units.</p>
<p>The overseas companies sold a total of 98,000 commercial 
vehicles (1995: 102,400). While sales were down 24% to 
28,800 units at Mercedes-Benz do Brasil because of the 
weakness of the market on the whole, they rose 69% at 
Mercedes-Benz Argentina, reaching 5,400 units. Thanks to a 
high order backlog, Freightliner was able to increase its sales 
by another 4% to 59,000 units, in spite of the cyclical 
downturn of the North American market for heavy-duty 
trucks. At Mercedes-Benz Mexico sales were up 43% to 
1,600 units as compared with the very weak situation one year 
earlier.</p>
<p>In the first nine months of 1996, commercial vehicle 
production at Mercedes-Benz totaled 246,100 units, which 
was slightly under the previous year&#146;s level. A total of 154,900 
vehicles were produced in Europe and 91,200 at our overseas 
plants.</p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p align=center><img src="../../lines/db_592.gif" align=bottom width=592 height=16></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table>
<tr><td align=center width=550><h5><a href="merced_g.htm">[&#160;<i>Deutsch</i>&#160;]</a> <a href="../../index_e.htm">[&#160;<i>Home</i>&#160;]</a> <a href="../facts_e.htm">[&#160;<i>Facts &amp; Figures</i>&#160;]</a> <a href="dasa_e.htm">[&#160;<i>Next</i>&#160;]</a> <a href="../../search/search_e.htm">[&#160;<i>Search</i>&#160;]</a> <a href="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&#160;<i>Dialog</i>&#160;]</a> <a href="../../help/help_e.htm">[&#160;<i>Help</i>&#160;]</a> </h5>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
