<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Product development on the computer screen</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61223_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Product development on the computer screen</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61230.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61230.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, December 30, 1996</i><br>The drawing-board of our day and age takes the form of the computer screen in combination with CAD (computer-aided design): scale drawings are no longer laboriously constructed with a pencil and ruler on paper, but arise on the screen at the click of a mouse.<p>The Daimler-Benz researchers have developed a computer programme which con-erts product-relevant CAD data into a variable three-dimensional projection within a matter of seconds. This tool, which facilitates the investigation of component installation and removal and the verification of dimensions and fitting clearances, greatly expedites the development of new products.<p>With this software, all original CAD data - irrespective of its origin - is fed to the computer. The programme can integrate data from various CAD systems, at the same time presenting it in visual form. The projection of a CAD model can be rotated, or modified in other ways, on a real-time basis - i.e. without delay due to computation. Cross-sections can be presented, for instance; individual components can be removed or exploded views generated, and the viewer can even "fly through" the model.<p>For the presentation of data within the computer programme, the researchers have selected two models with which modifications to an object can be carried out in real time. The so-called "advanced b-rep" (boundary representation) model makes use of all data acquired, whilst the "faceted" model makes do with a much smaller volume of data for presentation on the computer screen. A constant link exists between the individual facets and the precise b-rep model, so that the calculations required for rotating or otherwise modifying the model are based on the precise b-rep model at all times.<p>Computer-aided design (CAD) in the development of new products dispenses with the need for making scale models: with the help of CAD data, objects can be presented on screen in three-dimensional form. With the development of CAD software, the Daimler-Benz researchers are helping expedite this process.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61230_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61223_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 12/30/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
