<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Photoelectric cells - small is beautiful</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61217_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Photoelectric cells - small is beautiful</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61217.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=100 border=0 SRC="pics/61217.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=100 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, December 23, 1996</i><br>What looks like an immense seven-armed candelabra is in fact tiny and highly sensitive to light: a new-generation light detector developed by the Daimler-Benz researchers.<p>This light detector, designed on the basis of gallium-arsenide semiconductor material, consists of an array of individual photoelectric cells - so-called nanostructures. These cells, which take the form of interconnected channels of conducting material, are only a thousandth of a millimetre across. The researchers have ascertained that light has a highly sensitive effect on the conductivity of these narrow channels; this effect can be utilised in the development of a new type of light sensor with a high degree of internal amplification.<p>The small structural size of the individual photosensitive pixels (photoelectric cells) opens up interesting opportunities for application as light sensors in the form of a pixel array - for image analysis in road traffic, for instance, or as an "artificial eye" for multimedia applications. The detector properties of the individual nanosensors (pixels) can be readily influenced by modifications to their lateral geometry. In addition to these qualities, the new component from Daimler-Benz Research is distinguished above all by its ease of manufacture.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61223_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61217_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 12/23/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
