<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN"><html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type"content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0"><title>Plants monitor air quality</title></head><body background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" text="#000000"link="#2060A0" vlink="#606060" alink="#E0E0FF"><p align="center"><a href="../../index_e.htm"><imgsrc="../../icons/db_home.gif" border="0" width="89" height="33"></a><a href="../news_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/researkl.gif"border="0" width="54" height="44"></a> <a href="61218_e.htm"><imgsrc="../../icons/menu_rig.gif" border="0" width="54" height="44"></a><a href="../../search/search_e.htm"><imgsrc="../../icons/db_such.gif" border="0" width="54" height="44"></a><a href="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/mailkl.gif"border="0" width="54" height="44"></a> <ahref="../../help/help_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/helpkl.gif"border="0" width="54" height="44"></a> <br><img src="../../lines/db_592.gif" width="592" height="16"></p><p align="center"><font size="5"><b>Daimler-Benz and the&quot;Bel&egrave;m Project&quot;</b></font></p><p align="center"><font size="4"><b>Description</b></font><fontsize="6"><b> </b></font></p><div align="center"><center><table border="0">    <tr>        <td valign="top" width="380">The &quot;Bel&egrave;m        project&quot; &#150; a research project in the Amazon        delta which embraces social, ecological and economic        elements &#150; has now been in existence for five years.<p><b>History</b></p>        <p>In 1991 Bel&egrave;m University, in the Brazilian federal        state of Par&sdot;, and its &quot;ambassador&quot;, Willi        Hoss, former Daimler-Benz Works Council member and        Bundestag deputy for the Green Party, approached        Daimler-Benz and its Brazilian subsidiary Mercedes-Benz        do Brasil in S"o Paulo with a request for support.</p>        <p>The university was planning a research project        entitled &quot;POEMA &#150; Programa Pobreza e Meio        Ambiente na Amaz&Ugrave;nia&quot; (Poverty and Environment in        Amazonia), an ecological restoration project aimed at        persuading the indigenous population to settle        permanently in the region and enabling them to make a        living from the rainforest. It was, they argued, a        project which could help prevent further destruction of        the Brazilian rainforest, which &#150; it is now        recognised &#150; is so important for the stability of        the global climate. </p>        <p>The main question directed at Daimler-Benz was whether        the technological expertise of Daimler-Benz /        Mercedes-Benz do Brasil could be used to find a method of        processing the natural materials of the rainforest using        &quot;appropriate technologies&quot; and whether the        company might also be interested in making use of such        raw materials.</p>        <p>Daimler-Benz and Mercedes-Benz do Brasil joined in        this project, supplying financial and technological        support from mid-1992 onwards for a period of three years        in conjunction with UNICEF. During that period, the        Daimler-Benz group provided funding to the tune of 1        million US dollars &#150; in addition to its own research        costs and other technological expenditure, especially the        &quot;Tecnologia Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot; project launched by        Mercedes-Benz do Brasil and the work undertaken by        Daimler-Benz Research.</p>        <p>Since the completion of the first phase in mid-1995,        the project has continued to run under the aegis of the        University of Bel&egrave;m and Daimler-Benz, and has received        further financial and technological support from        Daimler-Benz. The aim of the 1995 to 1997 phase is to        explore the scope for utilising natural products such as        natural fibres for reinforcement materials and for using        vegetable oils and resins to produce constituent        components for plastics.</p>        <p>From 27th to 29th November 1996, with financial        support from Daimler-Benz, the POEMA programme is        organising a scientific congress in Bel&egrave;m on the scope        for technology transfer to other tropical regions of the        world &#150; and this has attracted participants from all        parts of the globe.</p>        <p><b>The challenge of the &quot;Bel&egrave;m Project&quot;</b></p>        <p>Three main requirements had to be fulfilled if the        project was to have any success:</p>        <p>1. First, cleared areas had to be re-forested in such        a way as to ensure continuous yield in the form of fruit,        fibre and wood and to allow several &#150; if possible        different &#150; harvests per year.</p>        <p>2. A permanent supply of water had to be made        available, in order to provide a further incentive for        the inhabitants not to leave their homes again        (normalisation).</p>        <p>3. In relation to the question of yields, there had to        be scope for making industrial use of raw materials        derived from the forest.</p>        <p>The project succeeded in finding appropriate solutions        to all three problems.</p>        <p><b>1. The &quot;agro-forestry system&quot; in Bel&egrave;m</b></p>        <p>The project launched by the university, under the        aegis of POEMA project leader Prof. Dr. Thomas Mitschein,        aimed at scientific re-forestation of environmentally        damaged regions. Small communities were identified whose        inhabitants were interested in new forms of        afforestation. The land made available was divided up        into plots 20 x 20 metres in size.</p>        <p>The &quot;agro-forestry principle&quot; can be        described in simple terms as follows: in the centre of        each plot, a particularly tall tree was either already        growing or was specially planted &#150; for example a        mango or Brazil nut tree. Around these, trees and shrubs        were planted according to agro-forestry rules, ensuring        that, depending on the species, the higher trees offered        a greater or lesser degree of protection from the sun.        Thus a mixed tropical forest was created, with several        &quot;layers&quot; such as are typical of the rainforest.</p>        <p>This kind of mixed forest &#150; which is, of course        not a natural rainforest and is in fact more like our        normal commercial woodland &#150; includes coconut palms,        cocoa trees, coffee and uruc. bushes. It is a mix of        plants which is suited to the fertility of the soil and        which also enables a variety of products to be harvested        and slash-and-burn techniques to be avoided. Furthermore,        the range of plants creates a new layer of humus in the        long term, which in turn prevents soil erosion.</p>        <p><b>2. Clean water: an essential element in the project</b></p>        <p>In the municipality of Praia Grande in Ponta de        Pedras, on the island of Maraj&Ucirc;, a water station was        established consisting of an elevated tank, a        wind-powered water pump and a solar plant to which an        electrolysis unit is attached. A solution of water and        sodium chloride is passed through the cell, which        releases germicidal hypochloride, which is then pumped up        to the tank.</p>        <p>It should be emphasised that the government of the        federal state of Par&sdot; has undertaken to set up 1,047        such treatment plants in rural communities which do not        at present have a clean water supply.</p>        <p><b>3. Industrial aspects of POEMA: the example of        &quot;fibres&quot;</b></p>        <p>The possibility of making industrial use of renewable        raw materials from the &quot;rainforest&quot; provoked        genuine interest within the Daimler-Benz group.        Experiments in S"o Paulo, Ulm and Stuttgart looked in        particular at the usefulness of natural fibres &#150;        especially coir (coconut fibre) &#150; for automotive        production. </p>        <p>Once it was established that they could, indeed, be        used in principle, the next question to be answered was        whether &#150; and at what cost &#150; the raw materials        could be acquired in the Amazon delta and could at least        be protected against rotting. In addition, it had to be        established to what extent it would be feasible to        process the materials in the Amazon delta itself, in        order to increase the local value-added element.</p>        <p>There were two further considerations: the end product        had to compare favourably with conventional materials in        terms of cost; and the equipment and plant required for        conservation and processing had to meet the criterion of        being &quot;appropriate technology&quot; &#150; i.e. they        had to be capable of being maintained and repaired on the        spot by local staff. </p>        <p>A considerable amount of literature had to be examined        in order to formulate the necessary research objectives.</p>        <p>Realising that the usefulness of such fibres as        industrial materials had been underestimated in the past,        Daimler-Benz quickly developed an extensive research        programme entitled &quot;Renewable Raw Materials&quot;.        Within a few years such natural fibres were increasingly        being used in motor vehicles. (In the case of Brazilian        factories, raw materials from the rainforest were used,        and in German ones, fibres from domestic cultivation, for        example flax and hemp.)</p>        <p><b>Headrests made of coir fibre</b></p>        <p>Shortly after the project was established, the        inhabitants of the settlement of Praja Grande on the        Amazon island of Maraj&Ucirc; began supplying Mercedes-Benz do        Brasil in S"o Paulo with headrests made of coir fibre.        Once removed from the external mantle of coconuts by        simple technical means, the fibres are processed into        cords before being conveyed to the small head restraint        factory, where they are combined with natural rubber        (latex) and formed into headrests.</p>        <p>The processes of removing the fibres, making the cords        and ultimately creating the headrests are carried out by        the locals, working within a cooperative. Every week        another family is &quot;on duty&quot;.</p>        <p>The individual production processes have now been        refined and optimised by the locals. Thus, for example,        they have developed simple industrial techniques for        removing the fibres from the fruit. They have also        improved efficiency in cord-making to such an extent that        production has increased ninefold from 3 kg to 26 kg per        day. </p>        <p>And they have come up with their own ideas for        improving and facilitating production of the headrests        themselves.</p>        <p>The cooperative in Praja Grande now supplies        Mercedes-Benz with some 2,500 headrests per month (30,000        per year). The costs involved &#150; including transport        from the Amazon basin to S"o Paulo &#150; are marginally        lower than those of producing components from man-made        materials. If one takes ecological aspects into account        (recycling) &#150; as is standard practice at        Daimler-Benz nowadays &#150; then production on Maraj&Ucirc;        is highly competitive. </p>        <p><b>Acceptance and involvement</b></p>        <p>The high degree of acceptance with which the project        has met is demonstrated by the way it has been extended.        In 1992, one municipality took part in POEMA, with 50        families among the inhabitants of Praja de Grande, a        small settlement on the island of Maraj&Ucirc; in the Amazon        delta, close to the city of Bel&egrave;m with its 1,400,000        inhabitants.</p>        <p>In 1996, some 35 municipalities were participating in        the projects, with about 2,000 families. An increasing        number of inhabitants of neighbouring settlements are        currently seeking information directly from the project        partners, in order to secure as many economic advantages        for themselves as well. The expected snowball effect has        become a reality.</p>        <p>Thus POEMA, in conjunction with Daimler-Benz AG and        Mercedes-Benz do Brasil, has paved the way for the        development of innovative forms of cooperation between        very different partners which can benefit the inhabitants        of the region and help reduce the burden on the        rainforests. The Bel&egrave;m congress has been planned as a        forum which will demonstrate to partners from the spheres        of science, industry and politics how similar action can        be taken and this approach extended &#150; on as global a        scale as possible. </p>        <p><b>Evaluation</b></p>        <p>The project has demonstrated how people in one of the        poorest regions on earth can be given the prospect of        survival in the future. It has also clearly refuted some        of the most frequently heard prejudices, for example that        people in such poor regions are not capable of bettering        their own situation.</p>        <p>Today the people of Praja Grande are &#150; relatively        speaking &#150; rich. They are now doing more than just        selling coconuts on the market, and Mercedes-Benz's        purchasing of headrests has become a major source of        income for them. In addition to this, further income is        generated by harvesting other products from the new        forest over the course of the entire year. </p>        <p>The success and the new social status it has        engendered have created a stronger sense of        self-confidence. The locals are now coming up with their        own ideas for modifying the forest cultivation methods        and have successfully introduced improvements into the        production processes as well.</p>        <p>The inhabitants of the region are now looking to        further improve their quality of life. The have acquired        a wind generator, which for the first time will provide        them with electricity; this environmentally compatible        technology helps reduce the cost of processing the        fibres. And of course electricity will also bring further        advantages such as refrigerators.</p>        <p><b>Mercedes-Benz and renewable raw materials</b></p>        <p>Mercedes-Benz has been quick to convert its        recognition of the potential offered by renewable raw        materials into actual production. Increasing numbers of        vehicle components now incorporate these materials. </p>        <p>The following components in the C-Class are already        being made from renewable raw materials (grown in        Germany):</p>        <table border="1" cellpadding="4" width="500">            <tr>                <td width="50%">Boot structure</td>                <td width="50%">Cotton fibre composite material</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Front seat-back</td>                <td width="50%">Coir fibres, animal hair, <br>                natural rubber (latex)</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Rear seat-back</td>                <td width="50%">Cotton fibre composite material</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Sound insulation elements in                transmission tunnel</td>                <td width="50%">Cotton fibre composite material</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Sound insulation (dashboard)</td>                <td width="50%">Cotton fibre composite material</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Lower covering of dashboard</td>                <td width="50%">Cotton fibre composite material</td>            </tr>        </table>        <p>&nbsp;</p>        <p>Mercedes-Benz do Brasil is currently using or        investigating the following components made from natural        materials in its commercial vehicle production:</p>        <table border="1" cellpadding="4" width="500">            <tr>                <td width="50%">Cabin interior trim</td>                <td width="50%">Jute and cotton fibre, sisal                fibre instead of fibreglass</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Seat-back and headrests</td>                <td width="50%">Coir fibre with natural rubber</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Dashboard</td>                <td width="50%">Sisal fibre instead of fibreglass                and natural polyhydric alcohols</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Tyres</td>                <td width="50%">Natural rubber</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Wheel covers, air and fuel lines</td>                <td width="50%">Natural polyamides</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Heat and sound insulation</td>                <td width="50%">Jute or cotton fibre</td>            </tr>        </table>        <p>&nbsp;</p>        <p>Further processes utilising natural materials are        currently under development:</p>        <table border="1" cellpadding="4" width="500">            <tr>                <td width="50%">Protective paint for engine</td>                <td width="50%">Based on indigo pigments</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Vehicle bumpers</td>                <td width="50%">Jute, sisal or ramie fibre,                together with natural thermoplastics (replacing                fibreglass)</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Sun visors</td>                <td width="50%">Coir or sisal fibre with natural                thermoplastics</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Paint</td>                <td width="50%">Based on natural dyes</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="50%">Tool box</td>                <td width="50%">Plant-based leather (cotton with                natural rubber)</td>            </tr>        </table>        </td>    </tr></table></center></div><p align="center"><br><img src="../../lines/db_592.gif" width="592" height="16"></p><div align="center"><center><table border="0">    <tr>        <td align="center" width="550"><h5><a href="61218a_g.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Deutsch</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Home</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Research &amp;        Technology</i>&nbsp;]</a> <a href="61218_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Next</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Search</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Dialog</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Help</i>&nbsp;]</a>        </h5>        </td>    </tr></table></center></div><div align="center"><center><address>    &#169; Daimler-Benz, last update: 12/18/1996</address></center></div></body></html>
