<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN"><html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type"content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0"><title>Plants monitor air quality</title></head><body background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" text="#000000"link="#2060A0" vlink="#606060" alink="#E0E0FF"><p align="center"><a href="../../index_e.htm"><imgsrc="../../icons/db_home.gif" border="0" width="89" height="33"></a><a href="../news_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/researkl.gif"border="0" width="54" height="44"></a> <a href="61218a_e.htm"><imgsrc="../../icons/menu_rig.gif" border="0" width="54" height="44"></a><a href="../../search/search_e.htm"><imgsrc="../../icons/db_such.gif" border="0" width="54" height="44"></a><a href="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/mailkl.gif"border="0" width="54" height="44"></a> <ahref="../../help/help_e.htm"><img src="../../icons/helpkl.gif"border="0" width="54" height="44"></a> <br><img src="../../lines/db_592.gif" width="592" height="16"></p><div align="center"><center><table border="0">    <tr>        <td valign="top" width="380"><font size="4"><b>Tecnologia        Ecol&Ucirc;gica &#150; A working programme of Mercedes-Benz do        Brasil as a contribution towards protecting the        environment and natural resources</b></font><p><i>Dr.        Ferdinand Panik, Director of Product Development,        Mercedes-Benz do Brasil S. A., S"o Paulo, Brazil</i></p>        <p>S"o Paulo/Bel&egrave;m, November 1996. &quot;Tecnologia        Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot; &#150; under this title, Mercedes-Benz        do Brasil presented its plan of activities for the        realisation of environment-friendly concepts for its        products and manufacturing plants in 1992. The        significance of this programme lies above all in the        design and application of new technologies, systematic        analyses and solutions as well as international        cooperation between the industrialised and threshold        countries.</p>        <p><b>In retrospect</b></p>        <p>In the years from 1952 to 1956, the Brazilian        government invited the international automotive        manufacturers to invest in Brazil and to establish an        efficient automotive industry. The potential of this        country &#150; with a territory larger than the USA        (excluding Alaska), a population at the time of 54        million (now 162 million) and the high transport        requirements of an agriculturally oriented economy &#150;        prompted a rapid reaction, which within only a few years        brought about the establishment of an automotive        manufacturing and supply industry in Brazil under the        aegis of American and European enterprises. This        breakthrough formed the backbone of the subsequent        upswing in the entire industrial sector, the construction        industry and the spheres of trade and banking &#150; and        the situation remains unchanged today. We in S"o Paulo        are quite proud of the fact that we are now the world's        largest German industrial city, measured on the basis of        the number of local German companies and the size of        their workforce.</p>        <p>This phase of Brazil's industrial development thus        constitutes an example of international cooperation, as a        result of which the Brazilian automotive industry        currently enjoys a strong position and &#150; with an        export volume of over 18,000 units annually &#150;        represents a major factor in Brazil's positive export        balance.</p>        <p>Daimler-Benz has played a formative role in this        success story. Having been on the scene in S"o Paulo        since 1955 as the first European automotive manufacturer,        Daimler-Benz introduced the diesel engine to the country        as a technological contribution; thanks to its highly        economical operation, this engine has held its own in the        commercial vehicle sector against the petrol engines of        the American companies Ford and GM, and it has maintained        market leadership ever since 1969 with a share of over        50% of all commercial vehicle engines produced in Brazil.</p>        <p><b>A symbiosis </b></p>        <p>The preparations for cooperation with a country on the        threshold of modern industrial development and the        application and transfer of promising modern technologies        has paid off for Daimler-Benz in the form of success in        this country, but also through the feedback of expertise.</p>        <p>The &quot;heavy-duty&quot; requirements of a country        like Brazil &#150; characterised by high operational        demands such as economy, low costs, low downtimes, low        maintenance, ease of repairs, in harsh conditions of        operation resulting from bad road conditions and        consequent requirements for off-road mobility,        overloading capability, high-altitude mobility and        long-distance operations &#150; have brought about        product and component developments which differ greatly        from those to be found under European conditions.</p>        <p>The Daimler-Benz group has benefited from the        successful establishment of this &quot;heavy-duty&quot;        production in Brazil: with Brazilian products, is has        conquered the markets of those southern hemisphere        countries which could no longer be serviced with European        products (costs, technologies). In this world region,        too, market leadership in the category of commercial        vehicles in excess of 6 tonnes has thus been maintained.</p>        <p><b>&#132;Tecnologia Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot;</b></p>        <p>From this macroscopic survey of the international        cooperation between industrialised and developing        countries, their historical development and its fruitful        effect for both partners, let us now now turn our        attention to &quot;Tecnologia Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot;. In a        threshold country, exemplary and progressive behaviour in        the social, technological and entrepreneurial fields is        expected of a renowned industrial partner. This is        particularly the case with environmental compatibility.</p>        <p>Right from the start, Daimler-Benz has invariably        accorded prime significance to this matter in the design        of its production facilities in Brazil. Mercedes-Benz do        Brasil, which established the first emissions laboratory        in that country, has been actively involved in government        programmes for the development and testing of commercial        vehicle engines operating on the basis of alcohol,        natural gas and natural oils and is actively and        progressively working together with the government in        matters of environmental legislation.</p>        <p>All this leads us to the vision of &quot;technologies        with a system&quot; &#150; a holistic view of the        vehicle, transport and the environment, in which the        individual processes of product design, utilisation and        impact are transformed into sustainable processes which        ultimately bring about stable situations in the        interaction between industry and the environment.</p>        <p>In specific terms, for example in the design of        products in Brazil, this means:</p>        <blockquote>            <blockquote>                <p>1. Low-emission diesel engines (using the same                technologies as in Europe and the USA)</p>            </blockquote>        </blockquote>        <p>2. Gas engine development</p>        <p>3. Avoidance of hazardous materials (e.g. asbestos)</p>        <p>4. CFC-free systems and manufacturing processes</p>        <p>5. Noise reduction (in vehicles and production)</p>        <p>6. Reduced fuel consumption in operation (lightweight        design, aerodynamics, engine electronics etc.)</p>        <p>7. Recyclability and resistance to corrosion</p>        <p>8. Closed-circuit processes (operating fluids, waste)        and conservation of resources (energy, water, materials)        in the production process</p>        <p>9. The use of biomaterials </p>        <p>10. Emission surveillance in the service sector and in        the field</p>        <p>Expertise developed in Germany has been adopted in        many of these fields, in close cooperation with        Daimler-Benz and Mercedes-Benz. In some areas, impetus        was in turn given by Brazil &#150; e.g. in gas engines        and biomaterials, which the parent companies have also        been applying and pursuing for some years with increasing        interest. </p>        <p><b>The use of renewable raw materials</b></p>        <p>Within this programme, it is the use of renewable raw        materials which comes closest to the ideal of achieving a        permanently sustainable balance between the environment        and technology. In this field, the technological        materials cycle in component manufacture is integrated        into a natural materials cycle, which throughout all        stages &#150; the cultivation of the plants, the        extraction of the materials, the processing and        subsequent disposal of the components &#150; is in this        very state of permanent equilibrium with regard to        materials and CO2.</p>        <p>In 1992, a research programme was established between        Daimler-Benz and the University of Par&sdot; in the Brazilian        Amazon region. This programme &#150; whose four points of        emphasis are natural fibres, natural oils, natural dyes        and natural rubber/adhesives &#150; is concerned with the        extraction, processing and application of natural        materials. The rich diversity of Amazon flora is opening        up interesting new perspectives. Especially in the case        of fibre-reinforced plastics, natural fibres are in some        cases performing much more favourably than fibreglass        reinforcement elements with regard to elasticity of        bending and tension, splintering or lightweight        characteristics; they are also proving more        cost-efficient.</p>        <p>These positive characteristics have paved the way for        a rapid transition from the research stage to series        production. Jute and sisal fibre are used for passenger        compartment linings (e.g. roof, rear wall, doors) and        &#150; in conjunction with cotton &#150; in        thermo-acoustical insulation. Coir (coconut fibre) is        used for seats. </p>        <p>Developments in the area of natural oils are marked by        similar success. Castor oil is proving to be a good basis        for glues, paints, polyamides and polyurethane;        Mercedes-Benz do Brasil uses over 300 tonnes of this        material per year in polyamide brake linings for its        commercial vehicles. In collaboration with Glasurit, a        natural pigment is currently being prepared for        industrial application; resistant to temperature and        light, this pigment is derived from the indigo blue dye        of the feranil plant. </p>        <p>Whilst natural rubber (latex) is already in use (4,000        tonnes per year in MBBras products), the research        programme is particularly concerned with obtaining        biologically degradable natural rubber, e.g. on the basis        of sugar cane or banana trees.</p>        <p>Intensive research work is also being carried out into        achieving a high utilisation factor for plants: the        trunks or stalks are used for fibre and the seed for the        manufacture of oils or plastics; wherever possible, a        combination of both is used in the production of        bio-composites reinforced with natural fibre.</p>        <p><b>Environmental technology &#150; the third        technology wave in automotive production </b></p>        <p>The use of biomaterials constitutes an entirely new        field of technology in research, process engineering and        automotive manufacture. At the turn of the century, the        transition from the horse-drawn carriage to the        automobile succeeded through the use of classical        mechanical engineering technologies (mechanics,        thermodynamics and electrical engineering). The present        situation is characterised by the utilisation of        electronics and of information, communications and        computer technologies, with which a transition from the        automobile to the integrated transport system is being        effected (e.g. in the PROMETHEUS Project). </p>        <p>These two technology waves will be followed by a        third, which will be concerned with environmental        technologies: the transition from open-end processes to        sustainable closed-cycle processes. Not only        technological, but also &#150; to quite a significant        degree &#150; social aspects will have to be incorporated        into this process; i.e. a fairer distribution of both the        positive and the negative consequences of industrial        activity will have to be effected in sociological terms.</p>        <p>Of fundamental significance in this process will be        dialogue between industrialised and developing countries,        between poor and rich regions, along with willingness to        cooperate. Brief mention can be made here of one        particular consideration. </p>        <p>The retention of the tropical forest regions &#150; a        global environmental objective &#150; can definitely not        be effected if this at the same time amounts to        perpetuating poverty in these regions while securing        wealth and luxury for the well-to-do countries together        with a high rate of energy consumption and CO2 emission.</p>        <p><b>The project &quot;POEMA &#150; Poverty and the        Environment in Amazonia&quot;</b></p>        <p>Integrating technology in sustainable processes is a        process which must be negotiated in many small steps. One        such step is the utilisation of renewable raw materials.        This goes hand in hand with sociologically based projects        such as &quot;Poverty and Environment in Amazonia&quot;,        supported by Daimler-Benz. </p>        <p>In Brazil, there is a particularly wide economic gap        between the industrial centres in the south and the        agricultural regions of the north and north-east. One of        the consequences of this gap is an exodus, which is        having a particularly taxing effect on the cities: the        &quot;favelas&quot; &#150; the slums of the major cities        &#150; are constantly growing. This process can only be        halted if the basic conditions of life in the poorer        regions can be improved.</p>        <p>The project &quot;Poverty and the Environment in        Amazonia&quot; of the University of Par&sdot;, carried out by        Daimler-Benz with UNICEF involvement, has precisely this        objective.</p>        <p>Pilot projects in four selected municipalities of the        Amazon region are concerned with devising ways of        improving basic living conditions. The project comprises        the establishment of</p>        <p>&#150; a social basis &#150; developing communal        structures (administration, education, cooperatives) and        supporting the health scheme (water supply, sanitary        concepts, medical care)</p>        <p>&#150; a basis of agriculture and forestry &#150;        establishing a sustainable system of agriculture and        forestry for the planting, cultivation and harvesting of        crops <br>        and</p>        <p>&#150; the industrial basis &#150; providing for the        application and preliminary processing of plants into        industrial products (raw materials, semi- finished and        finished goods).</p>        <p>This concept of agriculture and forestry derives from        the ancient native Indian tradition of terrace        cultivation. In structural terms, it is based on the        tropical rainforest: a dense community of plants is        formed which afford each other protection against        excessive solar radiation, prevent the ground from drying        out and maintain humidity, thus helping avoid the        consequences of monoculture &#150; which has led to        extreme nutrient depletion &#150; and of slash-and-burn        techniques for the purpose gaining new agricultural land.</p>        <p>Quite importantly, the concept of economical crop        utilisation is based on the principle of retaining a        significant local value-added element; the products are        thus processed within the various rural communities. </p>        <p>This involves the use of adapted technologies, which        for the main part are based on home work and whose energy        and investment requirements are sufficiently modest to        allow this work to be carried out within individual        families and cooperatives. The initiative was launched        with the cultivation of coir for use in head restraint        elements.</p>        <p>The initial stages &#150; from obtaining the coir        fibre to the manufacture of semi-finished products &#150;        are carried out by the farmers' families. The further        processing of the semi-finished products, the application        of latex, drying and moulding the head restraints are        carried out by the cooperative at a central location in        Ponta de Pedra.</p>        <p>The first phase of this project, to the end of 1994,        provided for the production of 900 head restraints per        month, with an increase to in approx. 2,000 units per        month in a second phase in 1995. The project developed        well. Mercedes-Benz do Brasil is supplied punctually, the        quality is acceptable and the costs are at a competitive        level despite the long transport routes involved.</p>        <p>Following the conclusion of the first two phases,        further opportunities are being investigated both in        terms of quantity (supply of other Mercedes-Benz        locations or other automotive manufacturers) and in        product diversity (e.g. sun visors or floor mats).        Further possible applications of the cultivated materials        are being investigated in the laboratories of the        University of Par&sdot;, of Daimler-Benz AG in Ulm and of the        supplier companies' project partners in Brazil; as broad        a basis as possible is to be created by this means for        the economic use of the region's agricultural and        forestry products.</p>        <p>These projects in Par&sdot; have something of a pioneering        character: they can be &#150; and indeed should be &#150;        adopted in other regions of Brazil. In their general        objectives &#150; the utilisation of agricultural        products for industrial products and the development of        manufacturing concepts with adapted technologies in rural        areas &#150; they are indeed capable of being transferred        to other countries. (At the Ulm Research Institute,        favourable results have been achieved in investigations        now also being carried out into European plants,        especially flax and hemp.)</p>        <p>The objective of emphasising the concept of        closed-cycle processes in all areas of product design,        utilisation and impact &#150; in the sense of the        establishment of a &quot;Tecnologia Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot;        &#150; has led to new approaches in the development and        combination of technological material cycles, natural        materials cycles as well as labour cycles. In many areas,        this calls for a new way of thinking, in which        cooperation between industry and developing or threshold        countries in particular can prove very fruitful, since in        such cases the threshold countries can learn from faulty        developments in the industrialised countries without        having to repeat their mistakes themselves. New        approaches, which once having proved their worth can then        be transferred to other regions, can be initiated there        much more easily than in the industrialised countries,        whose more highly developed structures often prove an        impediment to versatility.</p>        <p><b>A successful example: natural gas buses in Germany</b></p>        <p>This principle is borne out by the following example.        One of the closed-circuit processes investigated also        related to the use of natural gas as a fuel for our urban        buses. </p>        <p>Methane can be obtained in the form of natural gas; it        can also be recovered from landfills, or is available as        &quot;bio-gas&quot;. In Brazil, for instance, bio-gas is        obtained from sugar cane chaff; commercial vehicles are        powered by this means for the sugar cane harvest. Natural        gas engines have been developed which emit hardly any        particulates and whose gaseous emissions undercut those        of the Euro II diesel engines by more than 50%. The 500        or so urban buses now in operation for Mercedes-Benz do        Brasil are arousing increasing interest worldwide,        especially in Europe.</p>        <p>In Germany, the first test fleet was already presented        and commenced operation in Hanover in 1994 on the        occasion of the International Commercial Vehicle Show.</p>        <p>&quot;Tecnologia Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot; represents the        endeavour to develop thoroughly ecological concepts which        are at the same time economically viable. By the same        token, it represents the endeavour to devise        &quot;technologies with a system&quot; and to implement        these in specific stages. </p>        <p>International cooperation, especially within the        Daimler-Benz group between the partners in the industrial        and threshold countries, has proved particularly        promising and will continue to provide the basis both for        industrial activity in Brazil and for the development of        future joint projects such as &quot;Tecnologia        Ecol&Ucirc;gica&quot;.</p>        </td>    </tr></table></center></div><p align="center"><br><img src="../../lines/db_592.gif" width="592" height="16"></p><div align="center"><center><table border="0">    <tr>        <td align="center" width="550"><h5><a href="61218b_g.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Deutsch</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Home</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Research &amp;        Technology</i>&nbsp;]</a> <a href="61218a_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Next</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Search</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Dialog</i>&nbsp;]</a>        <a href="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<i>Help</i>&nbsp;]</a>        </h5>        </td>    </tr></table></center></div><div align="center"><center><address>    &#169; Daimler-Benz, last update: 12/18/1996</address></center></div></body></html>
