llent recycling qualities.        Research projects launched by Mercedes-Benz are now        exploring the scope for using other natural materials        such as jute, banana, hemp or ramie.<p>A modern vehicle        like a Mercedes-Benz car consists of a huge variety of        materials, of which the best known are steel, plastics,        glass and rubber. But if you take a closer look        underneath the bodywork of a car you can find an        increasing number of new materials which one would not        normally associate with car manufacture: cotton, flax,        coir (coconut fibre), sisal and latex.</p>        <p>Back to nature. For some years now, Daimler-Benz and        Mercedes-Benz have been developing the use of natural        materials. In doing so they have been following the goals        of the Rio de Janeiro Environment Conference, which        called especially for careful, sustainable and        responsible use of raw materials. &quot;Renewable raw        materials help reduce consumption of traditional energy        resources such as coal, natural gas or oil,&quot;        explains Dr. Dieter Zetsche, Board Member of        Mercedes-Benz AG. &quot;This also helps reduce the impact        on the world's climate by cutting carbon dioxide        emissions produced in the combustion of fossil        fuels.&quot;</p>        <p><strong>Climate protection and recyclability: the        advantages of natural materials</strong></p>        <p>In fact, raw materials taken from the inexhaustible        supplies of Mother Nature have a whole range of further        advantages:</p>        <p>&#150; Vegetable raw materials can be regrown and are        therefore available indefinitely &#150; in stark contrast        to fossil resources.</p>        <p>&#150; Natural materials can be processed with minimal        impact on the environment and do not contain any toxic        substances.</p>        <p>&#150; Car components made from renewable raw        materials are recyclable and can be easily reused for        other purposes.</p>        <p>&#150; Materials derived from vegetable fibre meet the        same rigorous safety and quality requirements which        Mercedes-Benz imposes on all its automotive components.</p>        <p>So there can be no doubt that renewable raw materials        have a great future &#150; not just at Mercedes-Benz and        not only in the automotive industry.</p>        <p><strong>Flax and sisal: new candidates for inclusion        amongst Mercedes' approved materials</strong></p>        <p>Mercedes-Benz is a pioneer in this area of materials        technology. Take the G-Class, for example. Although the        support for the rear window shelf and seat backs for this        model have already been made of natural fibre from the        very outset, a further &quot;natural product&quot; is now        used. It goes by the name of &quot;Flexiform&quot;, and        is used as a support for the door trim panels. It is thus        one of those many essential components hidden away inside        the body of a car whose existence most car owners are not        even aware of.</p>        <p>But Mercedes engineers put careful thought into even        these invisible components and are constantly looking for        innovations which bring advantages for the customer. Thus        it was that they came across two natural fibres which,        when combined, offer an excellent basis for the door trim        panel supports: flax and sisal.</p>        <p>&quot;At present, we use some 175 tonnes of each of        these two natural fibres. Our factories enquire some        4,000 Flexiform door trim panels every day, and these now        head the list of components made of renewable        materials,&quot; says Bruno Stark, Head of Materials and        Recycling at Mercedes-Benz Car Development.</p>        <p><strong>Shedding bulk and cutting consumption: Nature        helps the weight-watchers</strong></p>        <p>You can be sure that further uses will be found for        the flax-sisal mixture, for in addition to the        environmental benefits offered by this material, it also        has certain technical advantages which single it out from        other materials. The most important of these is weight.        &quot;When you are trying to cut down the weight of cars        and thus reduce their fuel consumption, every single gram        counts. Natural fibres have many pores but are still very        strong, and this often gives them an advantage in this        respect,&quot; explains Professor Guntram Huber, Head of        Bodywork Development at Mercedes-Benz. The Flexiform door        trim panels, for example, offer weight savings of 20%        over the material traditionally used &#150; and this adds        up to a savings of about one kilogram per vehicle. </p>        <p><strong>Harvesting and processing: from fibre to car        trim</strong></p>        <p>The flax fibre for the new door trim panels comes from        Germany. Bavarian farmers deliver it to specialist        textile factories which first of all separate the long        from the short fibres. This is necessary because it is        only the long fibres which are used to produce the linen        jackets, trousers, tablecloths and sheets sold by        department stores and textile retailers. The shorter        fibres &#150; some 10 to 50 centimetres in length &#150;        are mainly used for industrial purposes, by Mercedes-Benz        for example. In collaboration with its suppliers, the        company has developed a process by which domestically        produced fibre is mixed with sisal from overseas and made        up into mats a centimetre thick.</p>        <p>The next step involves special presses which, after        addition of a bonding agent, shape the flax/sisal mats        into the supports for the interior door trim. And here        another advantage of the natural fibres comes to the        fore: the process is not only easier and more        environmentally friendly than the usual materials, but        also offers greater scope for the designers, for the        flax/sisal mats can be formed into even the most        complicated shapes and curves &#150; in one simple        process.</p>        <p><strong>Quality and safety: flax/sisal combination        highly rated</strong></p>        <p>Supports made from Flexiform also scored very highly        in tests carried out in Mercedes' laboratories.        &quot;Compared to other natural fibres, the flax/sisal        combination has good mechanical characteristics,&quot;        states Uwe Siehler, development engineer at        Mercedes-Benz. &quot;The material passed our climate        tests, impact tests and quality inspections with flying        colours.&quot; As always with Mercedes-Benz, safety was        the most important aspect, and the engineers carried out        various different impact tests in an attempt to work out        how the natural material would behave in an accident. It        emerged that the flax/sisal supports are extremely        impact-resistant and do not splinter, so that in the case        of a side impact no sharp pieces penetrate the vehicle        interior and endanger the occupants. As Uwe Siehler put        it: &quot;Here, too, flax/sisal is superior to many other        materials.&quot;</p>        <p><strong>History and future: flax makes a comeback</strong></p>        <p>In the past, flax was the most important raw material        for the textile industry. In the Middle Ages, the Allg&auml;u        and neighbouring regions in southern Germany boasted        Europe's biggest concentration of these plants with their        bright blue flowers. But then came cotton, which proved        to be so powerful a rival that the acreage devoted to        flax in Europe shrank drastically. By the end of the        Second World War, flax fields were a thing of the past in        Germany.</p>        <p>It was only in recent years that flax has started to        make something of a comeback. There have even been times        when linen was one of the fashion industry's favourite        materials &#150; and the manufacturing industry has also        discovered many other possibilities for processing flax        fibre. Nowadays it is used not only to make post-office        bags but also shoe-making thread, non-woven fabrics and        even bank notes! At present some 1,700 hectares of land        are devoted to flax cultivation &#150; a mere ten years        ago, it was only two. </p>        <p>The other renewable raw material used for the interior        door trim of the Mercedes-Benz G-class is a genuine        recycled material. Mercedes' suppliers use the sisal        sacks in which South American coffee plantations send        their coffee beans to Europe.</p>        <p><strong>Cotton and coir: natural raw materials for        supports and seat cushions</strong></p>        <p>Apart from flax and sisal, other materials have also        started to be used in some Mercedes models in recent        years. Cotton and coir fibre, for example, have proved        useful at various points in the interior of the G-class.</p>        <p><strong>Research projects: good prospects for natural        fibres</strong></p>        <p>Other natural fibres are also currently under        consideration by researchers, and in a few years these,        too, may be fit for use in series production &#150;        either as raw materials for manufacturing automotive        components or as reinforcement in man-made materials. An        example of the latter would be a combination of a        thermoplastic material such as polypropylene and a        natural fibre such as flax or coir. This is stronger and        more easily recyclable than plastics reinforced with        fibreglass. The ultimate, of course, would be        &quot;bio-plastics&quot; produced from a vegetable base        like castor oil, reinforced with flax or coir fibres.        Researchers are already working on such developments.</p>        <p>The table shows which natural fibres are already used        in the automotive industry or are likely to be used in        the future.</p>        <p><strong>From banana to sisal: Excellent prospects for        natural fibres in automotive manufacturing</strong></p>        <table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1"        width="604">            <tr>                <td width="25%" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">Raw material</td>                <td width="31%" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">Origin</td>                <td width="44%" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">Possible uses</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="25%">Banana</td>                <td width="31%">Philippines, Central America</td>                <td width="44%">Reinforcement of polyester resins</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="25%">Cotton</td>                <td width="31%">Africa, China, USA, India,                Pakistan, Brazil, Russia</td>                <td width="44%">Manufacture of interior trims and                supports and sound insulation mats</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="25%">Flax</td>                <td width="31%">Germany, Canada, Russia</td>                <td width="44%">Manufacture of interior supports;                reinforcement of plastics</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="25%">Hemp</td>                <td width="31%">India, Thailand, China</td>                <td width="44%">Backing for carpets</td>            </tr>            <tr>                <td width="25%">Jute</td>                <td width="31%">India</td>                <td width="44%">