<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>An on-board computer that recognises road signs</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61126_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>An on-board computer that recognises road signs</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61203.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=90 border=0 SRC="pics/61203.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, December 3, 1996</i><br>Which way now? In view of the veritable forest of signs lining our roads, it is very easy to overlook the odd one or two - and if one of them happens to indicate a speed limit, we are sometimes made aware of the fact by the flash of a camera. As a rule, this costs a dollar or two and possibly a couple of points on the driver's record.<p>A system which recognises roadside signs and conveys this information to the driver would be of invaluable assistance. The Daimler-Benz researchers have already developed such am image processing system. A camera on the rear-view mirror monitors the surroundings of the vehicle, and the images thus obtained are evaluated on the basis of two salient features of road signs: colour and shape.<p>German traffic is regulated by about 400 different road signs, the predominant colours of which are red, blue, yellow, black and white. From the overall panorama, the image processing system initially selects prominent elements distinguished by these characteristic colours, after which it concentrates on those objects which are seen as even more likely "candidates" on the basis of their colour combinations and distinctive shapes.<p>Following this pre-selection process, the system then proceeds to search for the circular and polygonal contours highly characteristic of road signs. It finally compares this interlinked information with the images of road signs stored in its memory. Once identified, the sign in question is displayed on a small screen in the driver's area.This is all carried out by a high-performance computer located in the luggage compartment. The computer processes the visual information just as rapidly as the human eye and brain, but without lapses in concentration or signs of fatigue. The image processing system thus affords genuine assistance amidst the jungle of road signs.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61203_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61126_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 12/03/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
