<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Season's greetings from raw quartz</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61119_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Season's greetings from raw quartz</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61126.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61126.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, November 26, 1996</i><br>"...When the snow lay round about, deep and crisp and even." But there are no red Santa Claus hoods to be espied here between snow-covered pine trees, even on very close inspection. And this would indeed be rather surprising: what at first sight resembles a pine forest at Christmas time is in fact raw quartz. In this form, the material has been providing the basis for piezoelectric quartz research at Daimler-Benz AG for several years.<p>Piezoelectric quartz consists of pure silica in the form of small crystals. A high-frequency alternating electric field stimulates these crystals to a state of intensive mechanical oscillation; this is referred to as the inverse piezoelectric effect. Thanks to this characteristic, piezoelectric quartz has already been used for several years in the most diverse applications.<p>Piezoelectric quartz crystals serve to regulate quartz clocks and digital electronic systems; they are also used as transmitters or receivers in pressure sensors and electronic filters. But now especially, with Christmas rapidly approaching, it is not so much the components but the raw material itself which holds our attention; throughout the years of technological progress, it has lost nothing of its beauty and continues to create the impression of a winter landscape enshrouded in thick snow. </TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61126_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61119_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 11/26/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
