</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Lathing instead of grinding</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61112_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Lathing instead of grinding</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61119.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61119.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, November 19, 1996</i><br>To the accompaniment of a spine-chilling whirr, the grinding wheel delves its way into the hardened steel. An oil-water mixture sprayed between the tool and the steel provides lubrication; but the steel is so hot that some of the cooling lubricant evaporates and rises into the factory air, thus impairing the working atmosphere.<p>From an environmental point of view, cooling lubricants are not entirely "cool": since they are difficult to separate from the metal filings produced in the grinding process, they hinder recycling of the metal waste. Furthermore, they produce noxious vapours and sludges. The Daimler-Benz researchers hope to remedy this situation by working on a new method of machining hardened components which dispenses with the use of cooling lubricants. <p>It is above all due to the high circumferential speeds involved that in the conventional grinding of hardened components, large quantities of heat are produced between the grinding wheel and the workpiece; this necessitates the use of a cooling lubricant. With the new method - hard lathing with a geometrically specific blade, or simply hard lathing for short - considerably lower interface speeds between tool and workpiece are feasible. Moreover, some eighty percent of the heat produced in the lathing process is carried off by the filings removed. A cooling lubricant can thus be dispensed with.<p>The dry lathing of hardened components with geometrically specific blades has been made feasible by the development of new, superhard blade materials. The metal is no longer removed by a grinding wheel, but is shaved from the surface by a blade made from cubic boron nitride or a special ceramic material. Acquisition and disposal costs for coolant lubricants can be spared; and the filings produced are free from impurities, which makes direct recycling possible.<p>Along with the ecological aspects, however, the economic side of the new process must not be forgotten. The prime objectives of the Daimler-Benz researchers are achieving a satisfactory tool service life whilst maintaining the required component surface quality and further improving the process with a view to economic considerations.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61119_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61112_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 11/19/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
