<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The fuel cell - once an "extraterrestrial" energy system</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61105_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>The fuel cell - once an<br> "extraterrestrial" energy system</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61112.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61112.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, November 12, 1996</i><br>The cars move along silently. There are neither petrol fumes nor foul-smelling exhaust gases to pollute the air; in fact, the exhaust pipes which all too often used to discharge thick clouds of soot are nowhere to be seen. And the major winner is the environment, which is now burdened by exhaust gases only to a minimal extent, if at all. Whilst this may still seem something of a pipe dream - or rather, a non-pipe dream - it is the shape of things to come in automotive technology.<p>Alternative drive technology first took the form of battery-powered cars. But as has been shown by the Necar II research vehicle recently presented by Daimler-Benz in Berlin and by the World Hydrogen Conference in Stuttgart, fuel cell technology with hydrogen as an energy medium seems to be becoming an increasingly hot favourite as the drive system of the future.<p>Energy systems based on the low-temperature combustion of hydrogen are in fact old hat: so-called alkaline fuel cells have been used in space technology ever since the sixties. These cells owe their name to the electrolyte used - caustic potash, a solution whose extremely aggressive nature precludes this form of energy supply from everyday use in automotive technology.<p>Since only very few materials can withstand the corrosive effect of the caustic potash, this substance is difficult to handle. Furthermore, the electrolyte only makes for sufficiently long periods of operation if the air supply is free of carbon dioxide - a tall order in engineering terms. These considerations make alkaline fuel cell systems too expensive for everyday application. <p>Nevertheless, hydrogen technology is making an appearance on our roads. The development of high-performance membranes in the mid-eighties paved the way for a new generation of fuel cells. The flow of ions within the cell is now regulated not by an aggressive caustic potash solution, but by plastic foils. Here, too, the name of the fuel cell system is derived from the electrolyte - the proton exchange membrane, or PEM for short.<p>The Daimler-Benz research vehicle Necar II is powered by PEM technology. Compared with the alkaline fuel cell, these electrochemical cells are considerably easier to handle, with higher power efficiency levels. The materials used are also cheaper, so that costs can be kept to a level which will make the system affordable even to the average motorist.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61112_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61105_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 11/12/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
