<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Reinforcement with hemp</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61029_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Reinforcement with hemp</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61105.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61105.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, November 5, 1996</i><br>The hemp plant, alias cannabis sativa, is quite decorative. But some time ago, the misuse of cannabis as a hallucinogenic drug led to a ban on its cultivation in Germany: wherever it still did exist, it was on the "wanted" list. As of 1996, however, the cultivation of fibrous hemp - which produces only small quantities of the resin containing the ignoble drug - is now permitted again in Germany for industrial applications.<p>Hemp has long held the interest of the scientists from the Daimler-Benz Research Centre in Ulm. But it was only the relaxation of legislation in Germany relating to its cultivation that paved the way for intensive research. The scientists are currently investigating opportunities for using hemp fibre in place of glass fibre for the reinforcement of plastics.<p>In automotive applications, fibreglass-reinforced plastics are used in both interior and exterior vehicle components. The glass fibres embedded in the plastics, however, hinder the environmentally compatible disposal of disused components. For this reason, ecologically more suitable fibres such as flax are already being used in place of fibreglass - and more recently, hemp fibre has come into consideration.<p>The researchers have determined that hemp has a number of advantages over flax: it is excellently suited to processing, its fibres are more rigid and it can be cultivated without the use of insecticides. These advantages, however, would not be sufficient in themselves: in addition to being ecologically superior, hemp fibre must at least be on a par with flax in meeting the demands of safety, reliability, performance and comfort. Appropriate harvesting technology and standardisation of fibre quality, for instance, are still to be resolved.<p>Initial investigations carried out by the Daimler-Benz researchers have shown that in most criteria, hemp matches and even surpasses flax in terms of performance potential; and although precise statements cannot yet be made regarding costs, hemp fibre promises to be even more economical than flax.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61105_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61029_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 11/05/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
