<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>No mere decoration: heterostructural bipolar transistors</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61022_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>No mere decoration:<br> heterostructural bipolar transistors</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61029.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61029.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, October 29, 1996</i><br>The transistors shown here are somewhat more reminiscent of an arcade of Doric columns than of a semiconductor element. The salient feature of these so-called heterostructural bipolar transistors developed by the Daimler-Benz researchers, however, is not their aesthetic qualities, but their physical characteristics.<p>In the field of telecommunications in particular, the Daimler-Benz researchers are expecting an increase in demand for transistors with very high cut-off frequencies. The heterostructural bi-polar transistors developed at Daimler-Benz from the elements silicon and germanium (Si/SiGe-HBT for short) attain a frequency of 160 Gigahertz, or 160 billion oscillations per second - a world record. They also have the advantages of economy, low space requirements as a result of large-scale integration and low power consumption thanks to their high efficiency factor.<p>The market advantage of Si/SiGe heterostructural bipolar transistors over so-called III-V semi-conductors such as gallium arsenide or indium phosphide lies in the availability of the materials and the matured processing technology with regard to silicon. Further advantages are their natural oxide coating, which lowers the metal's reactivity (i.e. increases its passivity), and their high thermal conductivity, which makes for efficient heat dissipation.<p>According to the scientists, the advantages of Si/SiGe heterostructural bipolar transistors speak in favour of their use in such applications as cellular radio technology, which calls for large production quantities; the use of standard silicon production lines would keep manufacturing costs to a minimum.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61029_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61022_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 10/29/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
