<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Programmierbare Metalle</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="61015_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Programmierbare Metalle</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/61022.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/61022.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, October 22, 1996</i><br>I can remember exactly!" When uttered by a human being, such an exclamation is nothing out of the ordinary. But there are some metals, too, that could make such a claim - if only their exceptional memory were supplemented by vocal cords.<p>The remarkable characteristic of so-called shape-memory alloys - also known as "memory metals" - is their ability to repeatedly resume specific shapes following distortion. The Daimler-Benz researchers have been utilising this effect in aviation and space technology. Shape-memory alloys, however, are now also finding increasing application in the fields of automotive engineering, medicine, data processing and energy technology.<p>One objective of the Daimler-Benz research team is to extend the service lives of satellites. To this end, the scientists are now starting to use shape-memory alloys instead of plastics for the belts which serve to bind the low-temperature tanks to the exterior structure. Due to the reduced force of gravity encountered in space, the belts need only be tightened before and during the start, and not in the further course of operation. Thanks to shape-memory alloys, the belts can now be loosened in space independently of temperature, thus preventing the flow of heat towards the tanks. This brings about a drastic reduction in fuel consumption and extends the satellites' service life.<p>The shape-memory alloys currently being given the most attention are those based on nickel and titanium. A memory metal component subjected to distortion assumes its original shape on being heated to a specific "pre-programmed" temperature; this dependence on temperature is a result of the abrupt reorganisation of atomic structures into different crystalline lattices. In macroscopic terms, these transitions are perceivable as changes in length, volume or electrical resistance. The process can be reversed by cooling - the metal "remembers" its original shape in each case.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="61022_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="61015_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 10/22/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
