<HTML>

<HEAD><TITLE>New materials in engine electronics</TITLE></HEAD>



<BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF">

<P>



<CENTER>



<A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A>

<A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A>

<A HREF="61001_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A>

<A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A>

<A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> 

<A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A>

<BR>



<IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P>



<FONT SIZE=+2><B>New materials in engine electronics</B></FONT>

<P>



<table>

<TR>

<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380>

<A HREF="pics/61008.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=100 border=0 SRC="pics/61008.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=100 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif">

<i>Stuttgart, October 8, 1996</i><br>

What we see here are neither sea anemones nor the bases of uprooted trees, but in fact a field effect transistor incorporating a completely new class of semiconductors developed by Daimler-Benz: the so-called III-V components.
<p>

These components have two decisive advantages over those most frequently used today, the silicon (Si) semiconductors. They are considerably faster, which makes them suitable for application above all in the field of communication and sensor technology; and they can be designed with "tailor-made" optical and electrical characteristics.
<p>

These semiconductors owe their name to their chemical constituents - elements from the third and fifth main groups of the periodic system. Typical representatives are gallium arsenide (GaAs) and indium phosphide (InP).
<p>

The III-V semiconductor components open up a wealth of new opportunities for suppliers, manufacturers and users of sensor and communication systems. Developments include weather-resistant sensor systems in the field of vehicle safety.

</TABLE>

<P><BR>



<IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P>



<TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550>

<H5><A HREF="61008_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A>

