<HEAD><TITLE>Noise suppression on the boost air housing</TITLE></HEAD>



<BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF">

<P>



<CENTER>



<A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A>

<A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A>

<A HREF="60917_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A>

<A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A>

<A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> 

<A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A>

<BR>



<IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P>



<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Noise suppression on the boost air housing</B></FONT>

<P>



<table>

<TR>

<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380>

<A HREF="pics/60923.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60923.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif">

<i>Stuttgart, September 23, 1996</i><br>

The outline is perhaps reminiscent of a squashed stag beetle, and the pattern reminds us of a zebra: this is what the boost air housings of commercial vehicles look like when Daimler-Benz researchers set them into vibration.
<P>

These boost air housings, approximately 60 x 80 cm in size, develop strong sound propagation during engine operation. Only when the sources of this noise are located can specific measures be taken to reduce it.
<P>

The scientists are therefore using analyses of sound spectra to determine the precise frequencies at which strong noise develops. With the help of a physical measurement method known as holographic interferometry, the researchers then create a vibration image - the squashed stag beetle - for each of these so-called critical resonance frequencies.
<P>

With the help of the vibration images, which are a representation of the two-dimensional distribution of the respective vibrations from the boost air housing, the designer responsible can then modify the housing to eliminate noise-producing vibration patterns.

</TABLE>

<P><BR>



<IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P>



<TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550>

<H5><A HREF="60923_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A>

<A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A>

<A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A>

<A HREF="60917_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A>

<A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A>

<A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  

<A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A>

</H5>

</TABLE>



<ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 09/23/1996</ADDRESS><P>



