<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The fuel cell labyrinth</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="60820_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>The fuel cell labyrinth</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/60827.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60827.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, August 27, 1996</i><br>From one second to the next, grooves turn into humps and raised platforms are transformed into depressions; and just an instant later, the eye of the beholder turns a somersault once more as everything returns to its original condition. <p>This optical illusion is caused by grooves, like the passages of a labyrinth, which are milled into the surface of a graphite plate. About20 x 20 cm in size, this plate is a component of the so-called fuel cell, the core of the environment-friendly drive system currently under development at Daimler-Benz Research. <p>Two plates separated by an electrically conductive polymer foil together with an exterior circuit constitute a fuel cell. Hydrogen flows through the many tortuous channels on the one side of the foil, and oxygen from the air on the other side. The two gases react with each other through the polymer foil in the course of their protracted passage along the plates.<p>The reaction produces a potential of 0.6 V, which in turn gives rise to an electric current along the exterior circuit; at the same time, water is produced on the oxygen side of the foil. The power of 100 W developed by one single cell, however, is by no means adequate to drive a vehicle.<p>Sufficient power is produced only by a number of cells connected in series - so-called fuel cell stacks. In the Daimler-Benz research vehicle Necar II, two high-performance stacks each con-sisting of 150 cells together produce an output of 50 kW. </TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="60827_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="60820_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/27/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
