<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The removal team</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="60806_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>The removal team</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/60813.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60813.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, August 13, 1996</i><br>It is normally the bumpers more than any other component that emerge from a rear-end accident the worse for wear. In former times, dented chrome bumper-bars were a case for the scrap heap. These days, however, bumpers are of painted plastic and thus no longer suffer such an ignominious fate.<p>Scientists from the Daimler-Benz Research Centre in Ulm have launched into new dimensions in the recycling of painted plastic components. The advantages of their newly developed method is that the components are treated with great care, and the separated paint is returned to the production cycle.<p>Appropriate paint removal can be effected by environmentally compatible swelling agents, which swell the paint on the granulated plastic components and transform it into a paste-like substance; this can then be removed with weak rubbing forces. Using the so-called vibratory grinding technique, the scientists are capable of carefully removing the paint from the entire surface of the plastic bumper.<p>The further stages involve separating the plastic components, the paint particles and the swelling agent. In order to further process the paint, the scientists create conditions under which it is transformed together with the remaining swelling agent into a so-called polyol, a raw material used in paint manufacture. The cleansed plastic granules are recycled in the manufacture of new components, and the swelling agent is reused in paint removal. There are no resides left at the end of the process - the cycle for painted plastic components is complete.<p>In view of the paint quantities obtained through repairs and the return of disused vehicles, a yield of about four bumpers per vehicle can be expected on average. Paint removal using swelling agents ensures high-quality recycling of these plastic components.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="60813_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="60806_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/13/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
