<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Post-haste</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="60723_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Post-haste</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/60730.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60730.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, July 30, 1996</i><br>Even in this day and age of electronic media, receiving mail can still be a pleasant experience. But it can happen to a post office employee that he opens an envelope only to find not the expected love letter, but a flexible piece of microelectronics.<p>With the help of this electronic time-and-motion letter, the postal services can precisely retrace the path of mail items from the sender to the recipient and locate any weak points. The electronic time-and-motion letter constitutes the core of the so-called quality test system (QTS), a product of the Daimler-Benz subsidiary AEG Electrocom. The quality test letter fits into a normal C6 envelope and is externally indistinguishable from an ordinary letter.<p>Postal delivery services work to precise time schedules which require mail items to remain constantly on the move. This is the basis of the QTS measuring system. The time-and-motion letter constantly records its own movements throughout its journey. The measurements, presented in the form of an intensity/time graph, show a characteristic curve for each particular mode of transport - on foot, by car, by rail and by air. When these are compared with the time schedule, any weak points in the transport chain can thus be made out.<p>A long interruption to the letter's journey, for example, would be one such weak point. This would appear on the intensity/time graph as a "zero line" longer than is allowed by the schedule. With a resolution of as little as half a minute, this standstill can then be ascribed by the postal services to the clearing of the letter box, sorting at the post office of origin, renewed sorting at the destination post office or final delivery to the recipient, as the case may be.<p>Unlike conventional test procedures, QTS is a rapid, precise method which most importantly registers the entire delivery process - from the sender to the recipient - in order to allow delays in the transport of mail items to be pinpointed and these problems to be rectified. The quality test system is already used by several postal services, and according to AEG Electrocom, the interest in QTS is steadily increasing.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="60730_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="60723_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 07/30/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></