<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Transmitting and receiving en miniature</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="60709_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Transmitting and receiving en miniature</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/60716.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60716.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, July 16, 1996</i><br>Are these teddy bears' faces, gazing up to the heavens with their four big button eyes? Not exactly: they are radar sensors developed by scientists from the Daimler-Benz Research Centre in Ulm. <P>The active semiconductor component of the miniature radar chips is a so-called avalanche propagation time diode. In addition to emitting radiation themselves, the chips are capable of receiving reflected radiation thanks to the special characteristics of these diodes. Our photograph shows two such miniature radar sensor heads arranged at an angle of 90&#176; to each other; this configuration allows the simultaneous measurement of speed and distance by means of dual-frequency radar. Further uses of miniature radar chips with combined transmission and reception characteristics are as motion sensors, speed sensors and close-range radar sensors.<P>The miniature radar sensor head consists of a silicon chip only a few millimetres across, which is mounted on a round transistor casing; it is connected to the attachment lugs of the casing by two fine gold wires. The high-frequency circuitry with the avalanche propagation time diode is affixed to the chip by means of silicon millimetre-wave integrated circuit (SIMMWIC) technology developed by Daimler-Benz.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="60716_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="60709_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 07/16/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
