<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Polyurethane recycling: no sorcery</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="60702_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Tactile technology helps surgeons keep in touch</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/60709.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60709.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, July 9, 1996</i><br>There is not a sound to be heard in the operating theatre. The surgeon is handed a scalpel and proceeds to open up the patient's body. Contrary to expectations, however, he does not perform an elongated incision, but merely makes a small opening in the skin, through which he inserts a long endoscope. The operation has begun.<P>Scenarios such as this are no longer science fiction. An increasing number of developments in the field of minimal-invasive surgery are paving the way for such operations using long, rigid instruments under endoscopic control. With the so-called tactile forceps, researchers from Daimler-Benz AG - in cooperation with Dornier Medizintechnik and with Prof. Gerhard Buess and his team from the Department of Minimal-Invasive Surgery at the University of T&uuml;bingen - are making contributions to this field of research and thus to the comfort of the patient.<P>Endoscopic operations have one weak point as compared with conventional "open" surgery: they have to dispense with the functional unity of the surgeon's hand and his instrument - the surgeon thus cannot directly "feel" internal organs and surrounding tissue. And this is where the tactile forceps enter the scene: pressure applied to the instrument inside the patient's body is conveyed to the handle, where it can be "felt" by the surgeon.<P>The jaws of the forceps are fitted with an array of microsensors and a pressure sensor. When an object comes into contact with the jaws, the sensors measure the tactile impulses, which are processed and conveyed to the handle, where an array of actuators converts this information into a corresponding counterpressure at the surgeon's fingertips. The sensors and actuators thus induce tactile impulses in the surgeon's hand; this ensures safe, reliable endoscopic surgery.<P>The tactile forceps provide impressive documentation as to how the use of microsystems technology can provide tactile information for minimal-invasive surgery. The forceps also allow minimal-invasive palpation for the detection and location of pathologically diseased tissue. Large, compact organs (e.g. the liver or pancreas) can be examined just as conveniently as organs of more indeterminate shape (e.g. the intestines).<P>The tactile forceps reduce the burden placed on the patient through surgery. At the same time, they enhance the quality of patient care while reducing the risk of complications. Prototypes of the tactile forceps are currently undergoing clinical tests.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="60709_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="60702_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 07/09/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
