<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Polyurethane recycling: no sorcery</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../news_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/researkl.gif"></A><A HREF="60625_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Polyurethane recycling: no sorcery</B></FONT><P><table><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=380><A HREF="pics/60702.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=80 border=0 SRC="pics/60702.gif"></A><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=3 HSPACE=-2 WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=80 SRC="../../icons/abstand.gif"><i>Stuttgart, July 2, 1996</i><br>The gigantic glass retorts connected by an intricate system of glass pipes and clips conjure up images of a witches' brew. However, these are not the mystical doings of a sorcerer, but the work of the Daimler-Benz researchers, who are feeding soiled elements of foamed polyurethane (PU) waste into a recycling unit.<p>The chemistry of polyurethane recycling - so-called glycolysis - is by no means enshrouded in mystery; on the contrary, it can be put to use without difficulty for processing sorted PU waste. A mechanical trick has now enabled the scientists from the Daimler-Benz Ulm Research Centre to also recycle soiled foamed materials. PU waste from composite components, exterior panelling elements, seat padding and paint residues can thus be further processed for renewed automo-tive application.<p>And this is how it works. Prior to the actual conversion process, the scientists carry out pre-glycolysis. In a torsion reactor, two feed screws mix the viscous PU waste, which is heated to 180&#176; C, with glycol. This produces a "pre-glycolysate", the basis for further recycling. Without this preliminary treatment, the substances would soon stick to the reactor's stirring mechanism. Due to the high torsion exerted in the kneading process, the impurities are pulverised to a size of about thirty micrometres. At this size, the substances can no longer damage the stirring mechanism - finely distributed, they in fact prove useful as a filling agent for the plastic.<p>The recycled polyurethane from soiled waste elements can well stand up to a comparison with polyurethane components made from "fresh" materials. Mechanical characteristics such as bending resistance or impact strength are comparable with those of elements made from new raw materials. A preliminary cost estimate at Daimler-Benz has shown the recycling of soiled polyurethane to be quite viable in economic terms.</TABLE><P><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="60702_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../news_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Research &amp; Technology</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="60625_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>  <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 07/02/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
