<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental-Report `96 - Highlights: Recycling Electronic Scrap</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="15_1_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Recycling Electronic Scrap</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>A pilot plant in Ulm is turning ideas into gold: Thanks to a new multiple-step process, the plant can now reduce a computer circuit board down<br>  <TD width=5><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>to its individual constituents, making it possible to extract not only the harmful, but also the valuable raw materials that it contains.<tr><td><br></TABLE><p><a href="../pics/14_1.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/14_1.gif"></a><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Potential pollutants and<br>recyclates crowded together<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Computers are built on and around printed circuit boards. But once the useful life of a computer comes to an end, this vital entity becomes a significant problem: a board joins both valuable and polluting materials cheek-by-jowl in an inseparable unit. Until now the tendency has been to consign the boards-lock, stock, and barrel-to the garbage heap.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Pilot plant<br>in operation<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Thanks to Daimler-Benz researchers, however, electronic scrap recycling has just taken a significant step forward. By modifying and combining a number of different individual processes, the researchers have succeeded in reducing the boards to their material constituents. Indeed, a pilot plant using their process has already been running in Ulm for a few months now.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>A multi-stage process<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>The populated circuit boards are initially shredded, before being selectively comminuted at low temperature in the second stage of the process. A magnetic separator then removes the larger nickel and iron components from the coarse fraction. And once the dust particles have been separated from the fine fraction, the latter is then separated into plastic and metal fractions by means of dry mechanical separation. Once again, the iron and nickel components of the metal fraction are removed by the magnetic separator.<p><a href="../pics/14_2.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/14_2.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Purer materials,<br>lower emissions<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>In comparison to rival methods, this four-stage process offers a number of advantages: the metal recyclates are purer, and therefore easier to reprocess; the emissions are lower; no dioxins or furans are produced; and the process technology is simpler.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Valuable scrap<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>The recycling technique is also economically interesting. Costs of DM 300 to DM 500 per tonne of circuit board scrap give returns of DM 800 to DM 3000, depending on the gold content.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Still being tackled<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>One outstanding problem is how to reprocess the residual fraction with its high plastics component. Cracking this nut is now the task of Daimler-Benz's partner Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, which is already working intensively on a gasification and methanoly synthesis plant. The Japanese engineers can already gasify 99 percent of the residual fraction, although at present, the pollutant levels formed in this process are still significantly in excess of the levels permitted in Germany.<p><TD WIDTH=20><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="14_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Highlights</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="15_1_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
