<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental-Report `96 - Highlights: World's First Vegetable Oil in an Engine Plant</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="15_2_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>World's First Vegetable<br>Oil in an Engine Plant</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>A step towards the "clean" factory: Mannheim's new engine plant uses the latest biological<br>   <TD width=20><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>oils-so-called synthetic oil esters -which are kinder on both staff health and the environment. <tr><td><br></TABLE><p><a href="../pics/15_1.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/15_1.gif"></a><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>New Chance<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Whenever a new vehicle is being designed, or a new plant is under construction, opportunities for environmental protection emerge, not least because buildings, tools, and manufacturing techniques can be designed in an environmentally-sustainable way from the word go.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>DM 300 million invested<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Just such an opportunity at the Mercedes-Benz Engine Production Center in Mannheim was recently seized upon by the planners of the production facility for the new 900 series of diesel engines for commercial vehicles. Mercedes-Benz's investment in the construction of the pre-assembly area, the main assembly line, and the wide-ranging modernization of component manufacturing amounted to DM 300 million.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Biological oil<br>replaces emulsion<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>One major step on this particular route to reducing environmental strain was the introduction of a synthetic oil ester into the production process. Until then, the cooling and lubricating agents used in cutting processes, for example, where made up of an oil-in-water emulsion. This has now been replaced by biological oils. Consequently, Mercedes-Benz's Mannheim plant is the world's first engine plant to utilize such an oil ester in cutting processes.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Tandem project<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>The innovative and progressive firm behind this new family of biological oils is the Mannheim-based lubricant manufacturer FUCHS. Working in close cooperation with the machine tools manufacturing industry, FUCHS carried out extensive preliminary tests to investigate such things as the elastomer-compatibility of cabling and sealing compounds which are used for the machine tools and come into contact with the new ester oils.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Zero hazard<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>In addition, it is also possible to utilize these ester oils in the hydraulic equipment, and as lubrication for the bed track and gearing which are to be found in today's machine tools. Whereas traditional machine oils are generally made up of more than 90 percent mineral oil, the new synthetic esters are manufactured from vegetable raw material, and have been classified as totally harmless to water supplies. Moreover, the new oils have other advantages: unlike traditional water-in-oil emulsions, they are resistant to bacteria, which results in much reduced machine servicing. They also require less frequent changing, and therefore do not have to be disposed of so often. Finally, the disposal process itself is totally unproblematic.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Versatility saves!<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Thanks to their versatility, the ester oils can be used to replace cooling lubricants, hydraulic oils, and machine lubricating oils. They can therefore be utilized in a series of consecutive production steps which means that the wash processes between the individual production steps can be eliminated. The result is not only a reduction in cleaning agents, fresh water, and waste water, but also a lower energy requirement at the plant's clarification works.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Easy on the skin<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Last but not least, as well as marking another milestone on the road towards a better environment, the introduction of the ester oils is also much appreciated by the skin of staff working at the plant.<p><TD WIDTH=20><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="15_1_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Highlights</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="15_2_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
