<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Highlights: Bumper to Bumper</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="16_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Bumper to Bumper</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>Engineers at Daimler-Benz's Ulm Research Center have now built a small pilot plant<br><TD width=5><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>designed to handle the sophisticated recycling challenge posed by the modern bumper. <tr><td><br></TABLE><p><table><tr><td valign=top align=left width=380><a href="../pics/15_2.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/15_2.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif">Just like the mediaeval suit of armor, the simple pressed-metal bumper has fallen victim to the march of progress. The victorious advance of the aerodynamic, high-technology bumper system has led to increased traffic safety and reduced repair costs. Progress, however, has its price: in this case, a new problem for the recyclers. Exactly how do you dispose of a sophisticated mixture of 10 percent metal, 10 percent foam, 35 percent elastomers or thermosets, and 45 percent painted thermoplastics such as polycarbonate and polypropylene?<p>A few months ago, engineers at Daimler-Benz's Ulm Research Center broke the back of this problem. Their solution is a plant capable of separating and recycling all of the components up to a 0.5 percent dust and a 10 percent plastics residue fraction. Scaled up to handle 200 000 bumpers, such a plant would be able to produce raw material to the value of DM 30 from every bumper-for a processing cost of just DM 3.50.<p>This new process consists in fact of two separate stages: first of all, the preliminary mechanical preparation-including disassembly of the bumper bracket, cutting mill, grading, plus low-intensity and high-intensity magnetic separation; and, secondly, the chemical reprocessing, which involves removing paint from polypropylene and polycarbonate components, and separating polycarbonate and polypropylene blend in the dense-medium separator.<p>The latest advance to be achieved is in the paint removal process, which-as a result-is now even more environmentally-friendly. The reason: the barrel finishing plant now uses a new, completely non-toxic, two-component mixture in place of conventional swelling agents, which are a hazard to water supplies.<p></table><p><br><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="15_2_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Highlights</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="16_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
