<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental-Report `96 - Highlights: Ecological E-Class</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="18_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Ecological E-Class</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>Safer, roomier, and more comfortable than their predecessors, the new E-class models are in Nature's good books too: Boasting<br> <TD width=5><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>a variety of recycled and natural materials, they are also more economical, quieter, and produce less pollutants.<tr><td><br></TABLE><p><table><td align=middle><a href="../pics/17_2.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/17_2.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"></table><p><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Precious<br>catalytic converter<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>When it comes to cutting down even more on exhaust emissions, it's generally a job for high-tech know-how plus some rare metals. So it was that engineers developed a composite palladium/rhodium coating for the catalytic converter cells used in the four-cylinder E 200 and E 230 models. The result: warming up time is reduced which cuts down hydrocarbon emissions by up to 35 percent compared to conventional catalytic converters. In the new E 420, too, a computer corrects ignition timing and fuel supply so that the catalytic converter can reach optimal performance in a shorter space of time. As for nitrogen oxide emissions from the new diesel sedan, these have been cut by as much as half thanks to an oxidizing catalyst and recycling of the exhaust gases.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Less than 5 liters<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>And it's the same story for fuel consumption: compared to previous models, the new E class range is a real thrifty operator. Gasoline models are down by up to ten percent and the E 290 turbodiesel has even managed to crack the magical 5-liter barrier. With an average consumption of 4.6 liters per hundred kilometers at a speed of 90 km/h, one full tank of 65 liters will take you all the way from Berlin to Venice.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Slimming down costs<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Such savings on fuel are partly due to a commitment to light-weight construction. Thanks to high-strength steels, some alloyed with titanium, engineers were able to slim down the parts used. Although members of the E-class still weigh anything from 1.44 to 1.69 tonnes, the increased space that they offer means a relative weight reduction of up to 9 percent.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Minimal drag<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Low drag values (Cd values) also play a special part in curbing fuel consumption. At a value of 0.27 both the E 200 and the E 220 diesel outperform any other series production sedan. Authors of this particular success story are the engineers and designers who managed to quell even the smallest ripple of turbulence after testing a variety of different forms for the spoiler, external mirrors, rear window, radiator grille, front apron, sun roof, and the trailing edge of the trunk, where the airflow breaks away from the vehicle.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Even quieter<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>But environmental protection also means cutting noise pollution -which is why the Mercedes designers have been doing their best to make the new E-class quieter. And not without success: All models satisfy the strict EU standards in this area, with the automatic version of the E 220 diesel, for example, being 3 decibels under the specified level. In fact, the new models are no more than a quarter as loud as cars from ten years ago.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Recycled and<br>natural materials<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Last but not least, the E-class also incorporates a range of recycled and natural materials. Indeed, 17 components are already manufactured from natural materials: the interior door paneling is made from a flax/sisal mixture; driver and passenger are actually cushioned by natural mattresses filled with coconut fiber, animal hair, and latex; and trim for the arm rests and door pillars contains cotton, as do the supports for the rear parcel shelf.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>85 percent<br>re-use<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Although a car completely constructed from natural materials is still little more than a designer's dream, the fully recyclable vehicle could soon become reality. Around 85 percent of a Mercedes-Benz already flows back into the cycle of reusable materials. Moreover, thanks to the Mercedes-Recycling-System (MeRSy), used parts and materials are now being collected from service and repair workshops and recycled whenever possible.<p><TD WIDTH=20><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="17_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Highlights</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="18_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
