<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Highlights: Together with Euronatur</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Together with Euronatur</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>Thundering highways, noise and pollution-for many, mobility is inextricably bound up with the destruction of nature. Now, an unusual project promoted by Mercedes-Benz and the European Natural Heritage Fund (Euronatur) is showing how the rediscovery and preservation of traditional forms of mobility can also help to safeguard nature. "Naturally Mobile," -up and running since March 1995-aims to save five valuable historical regions from threatening structural change and to return them to a usage more in harmony with nature.<br><br><TD width=5><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>Mercedes-Benz's activities are part of a campaign organized by the Daimler-Benz group and Euro-natur, which-under the slogan "Mobility and the Environment"-uses earth-sensing satellites to monitor the earth's eco-systems. In alliance with Daimler-Benz, Euro- natur is also sponsor of a national parks program in the new federal states of Germany, chief example of which is the M&uuml;ritz National Park in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania, and of the Northern Sporades marine national park in the Greek Aegean.<tr><td><br></TABLE><p><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Extremadura,<br>Spain<br></B><br><a href="../pics/18_1.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/18_1.gif"></a><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>The Iberian peninsula is crossed by ancient long-distance paths which, since before the days of Don Quixote, have been used by shepherds driving their flocks to different regions in accordance with the rhythm of the seasons. In an initial project, two routes in the Extremadura are now to be protected and opened up to for a gentler sort of tourism. The first successes of this approach may already be seen. Recently, three shepherds with a total of 3000 sheep have again begun to use the paths-a first, important step towards establishing a new kind of conservation area: the world's first national trail park.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Provence,<br>France<br></B><br><a href="../pics/18_2.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/18_2.gif"></a><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Situated in southern France, hemmed in between the cities of Marseille, Arles, and Aix-en-Provence, lies the area known as the Crau. On closer examination, this barren steppe turns out to be veritable herb garden. Thyme, lavender, rosemary, and other herbs flourish there, as do rare species of fauna, including fourteen species of grasshoppers alone. Intensive farming practices, garbage dumps, a military air base, and monotonous peach plantations have made threatening incursions into the once 600-square-kilometer area. "Naturally Mobile" is doing everything within its power to preserve the remaining 115 square kilometers of breathtaking landscape.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Bremer Becken,<br> Germany<br></B><br><a href="../pics/18_3.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=125 border=0 src="../pics/18_3.gif"></a><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Encircled by a largely intact green belt, Bremen has long been the envy of other cities. Natural river plains, meadowlands, and flood plains such as those on the stretches around W&uuml;mme and Ochtum, where the River Weser has been restored to its natural state, provide a home for rare flora and fauna, plus a dust filter and oxygen source for Bremen itself. Located on the city's very doorstep, the Bremer Becken is also a priceless recreational area. Protection of this green belt-one of the aims of the "Naturally Mobile" project-will mean that the citizen of Bremen can continue to enjoy this rural tranquillity without having to burden the environment with journeys farther afield.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Green Bridges,<br> Hungary<br></B><br><a href="../pics/18_4.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/18_4.gif"></a><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Like many areas in the former eastern bloc countries, southern Hungary is threatened by intensive use. "Naturally Mobile" is seeking to preserve a network of intact biospheres and cultivated areas stretching from Lake Balaton to the Hungarian-Croatian border on the River Drava. This so-called "Green Bridges" project uses targeted regional management and controlled tourism to help set up conservation areas which can hold their own against the thriving economy.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>The Alban Hills,<br>Italy<br></B><br><a href="../pics/18_5.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/18_5.gif"></a><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Already in Roman times, the Via Appia connected the then "center of the world" with southern Italy. Today, relatively little remains from those days save a diverse, tightly integrated area centered on the community of Genzano di Roma. This continues to offer a haven to Romans seeking a break from the city's noise and smog. Here, alongside the Via Appia, the very stones are evidence of thousands of years of human mobility in harmony with nature-a combination which "Naturally Mobile" is working to preserve.<p><TD WIDTH=20><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="18_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Highlights</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
