<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Projects: Ecological Constructionon Potsdamer Platz</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Ecological Construction<br>on Potsdamer Platz</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>This trend is exemplified by the Daimler-Benz complex under construction in Berlin's Potsdamer Platz. No noxious vapors seep out from the construction materials used here. Blinds, too, shade the sun and replace the monotonous drone of the air-conditioning. In place of cold neon, natural light floods the rooms with warm illumination. A canny blend of complex engineering, modern thermal management techniques and well-tried ruses has conspired not only to create a pleasant working climate, but also to make immense energy<br><br><TD width=5><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>savings-a great environmental improvement on the construction techniques of the past. From day one, debis Immobilienmanagement called on the advice of a team of ecological construction experts from the firm Drees &amp; Sommer AG who also handle general management for the project. Once the building is ready for occupation, each tenant will receive an energy handbook produced by the firm, which lists all relevant energy information and provides tips on how to behave in an energy-conscious way.<tr><td><br></TABLE><p><a href="../pics/30_1.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/30_1.gif"></a><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><br><p><font size=+2><b>The energy-saving cornerstones of the building</b></font><p><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110> <B>Energy Supply<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>A modern Bewag gas and steam turbine power station provides the energy supply. Improving on the already sensational efficiency of this system, which boasts a 50 percent electricity yield, waste heat will also be exploited during the summer. District heating and cooling systems will supply the buildings on Potsdamer Platz. This reduces CO2 emissions by 70 percent-the equivalent of 48000 tonnes of this greenhouse gas-or the amount emitted from 9600 family dwellings.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110><B>Air Conditioning</B><br><a href="../pics/31_2.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/31_2.gif"></a><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Thanks to intelligent building design, the rooms do not overheat in the summer. Not only does this dispense with the need for air-conditioning, it also means that occupants can open windows as they please. And when it is too cold outside to do just that, a ventilation system sees to it that there's sufficient fresh air. In computing rooms, for example, where extra cooling is required, water chilled to a temperature of 18&#176;C circulates in cooling "ceilings". All in all, this means that heating and cooling requirements consume only half as much energy as would be required by a conventional air conditioning system.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110> <B>Heat Insulation</B><br><a href="../pics/31_1.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/31_1.gif"></a><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>With thick thermal insulation layers in the exterior walls plus thermal insulation glass instead of conventional double glazing, the buildings have a much higher thermal insulation rating than normal and use up to 30 percent less energy on heating.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110><B>Lighting<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>It is a well known fact that sunlight is not only free, but also induces a better frame of mind than artificial lighting. Planners therefore consulted lighting experts and, with the help of computers and scale-models of the buildings, devised ways of optimally using this natural source of light.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110><B>Water<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Given that the roofing of the complex stretches over some 50000 square meters, something had to be done to prevent rain water from just pouring down the drain-particularly after a downpour, when it overloads the water treatment works. Part of the water is soaked up by the vegetation planted on the roof, part tops up the lake by the National Library, and part is used to water the plants in the borders below. Anything left is used to fill w.c. cisterns. This represents a saving of 20 million liters of drinking water a year-the equivalent of 6500 crates of water every day.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110> <B>Building materials</B><br><a href="../pics/31_3.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/31_3.gif"></a><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>These were chosen according to environmental and health criteria. For example, only vegetable oils are used to lubricate the concrete shuttering; insulating materials are foamed with air instead of environmentally-damaging CFCs; tropical timber is totally taboo.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110> <B>Transport<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Together with the other investors in the Potsdamer Platz project-the Federal State of Berlin, Deutsche Bahn AG, Sony, and ABB-debis Immobilienmanagement has founded a company called Baustellenlogistik to manage the construction phase in the most environmentally-friendly way. A specially constructed bridge over the Landwehr Canal and a private road now link the site with the logistics center located in the Anhalt freight depot. Here, ships and railway freight cars-the two forms of transport least damaging to the environment-maintain the supply of building materials. This represents a saving of around 42000 truck kilometers a day, and also keeps the lid on dust and exhaust emissions-not to mention the tempers of the Berliners who need not face any extra traffic jams as a result of the construction work.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=110> <B>Groundwater</B><br><a href="../pics/31_4.jpg"><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=125 border=0 src="../pics/31_4.gif"></a><img vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=125 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Thanks to special "dry basement waterproofing" techniques, groundwater is hardly affected by the work. Compared to the so-called open water raising procedure, merely 5 percent of the normal water quantity has had to be extracted. Even so, 100 extra measuring stations monitor groundwater levels around the Potsdamer Platz.<p><TD WIDTH=20><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="30_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search/I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
