<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Projects: The Factory of the Future</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="27_1_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>The Factory of the Future</b></font><p>Ecologists too have had a say<br>in the design of an engine plant under<br>construction in the Swabian city of Bad Cannstatt. <br><p><table><td align=middle><a href="../pics/24.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/24.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"></table><p><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Green Roof<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Gerhard Winter, the environmental representative of the Mercedes-Benz plant in Untert&uuml;rkheim, indicates the sweeping roofs perched on top of the wide window fronts and gives his verdict: "I like the architecture. Our colleagues from the building department have done a first-class job." The building gives a strong impression of lightness and cheerfulness in its envelope of glass, steel, and stone. "Greenery will cover about a third of the roof areas," says Winter, above the rattle of a light railway train as it passes close to the site where the Bad Cannstatt engine plant is under construction.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>V6 und V8 engines<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Inside the huge hall, which measures almost half a kilometer in length and 120 meters in width, machines are being assembled in position. The thunder of a hundred hammers mixed together with the whine of drills makes conversation difficult-particularly, since Dr. Winter is soft-spoken by nature. But despite the bedlam the chemistry specialist's enthusiasm for the new center, which should be mass producing V6 and V8 engines for cars and off-road vehicles by October, is clear to see.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Integrated<br>environmental protection<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>And Mercedes is proud of more than just the aesthetic appearance of its "Factory of the Future." In particular, "integrated environmental protection" has enjoyed a high priority right from the start-something of a novelty for the planning team.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Lean plant<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>When finished, as well as being a "lean" operation, the Bad Cannstatt factory will be a place where responsible group work, low-cost production, and ecological sense go hand in hand. "Logistically seen, everything is in a line," explains Winter. The "raw product" passes through a series of interconnected machines and emerges from the assembly line as a finished engine. With each step in the process coordinated, resources can be used responsibly: less energy is required and less waste produced.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Team work<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Immediately following the decision to build the new engine plant in Bad Cannstatt, a team representing planning, production, and environmental aspects was put together to come up with ways of ensuring environmental considerations would be appropriately integrated into the factory design. That was three years ago, shortly after the Bad Cannstatt area of Stuttgart had successfully fought off competition from Lothringen. And Bad Cannstatt has excellent credentials-it is the place where Gottlieb Daimler and Wilhelm Maybach constructed the first fast-running combustion engine more than a century ago. Reflecting on the pace of developments over the last three years, Winter is quick to point out how "tight" the schedule has been.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Within the<br>catchment area<br>of mineral springs<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>The decision to use a contaminated site rather than a green-field one was clearly good news for the environment. However, it was first necessary to atone for the sins of the past: the site-a former German Railways repair yard located in a mineral springs catchment area-was saturated with pollutants.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Getting a lift<br>from building rubble<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>To protect the mineral springs, the building department had an ingenious trick up its sleeve. Utilizing reusable demolition rubble plus earth removed in tunnel construction for the Stuttgart subway, it was possible to raise the plant by one and a half meters. As a result, waste water simply flows away; pumping systems are unnecessary. Moreover, it was possible to construct the supply channels without interfering with the groundwater.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Sealed tub<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>The building team also managed to seal the production hall so thoroughly that it is impossible for liquids to escape. The roughly 3000-cubic-meter water catchment capacity is also sufficient to retain any water which may one day be used in a fire-fighting operation. The special concrete used for what Winter jokingly refers to as the "sealed tub" is impermeable to materials which are hazardous to soil or water because it is devoid of cracks and fractures-a fact confirmed in tests conducted by the Materials Testing Authority. The low-porosity material was integrated in layers under the watchful eye of experts. In fact, given that chemicals, oils, or lubricants cannot escape from the encapsulated machines, the sealed floor is really the reserve line of defense. <p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Gutters for all<br>eventualities<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>However, should such an event somehow occur, the liquids would be forced to flow from the hall floor, which is slightly inclined at two degrees, into catchment channels.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Special cycle system<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>For reasons of environmental protection and work safety, the mineral oils used exclusively as cooling lubricants at Mercedes are almost completely devoid of environmentally-harmful additives and contain no aromatic hydrocarbons, which do not degrade easily. CFCs, the cause of the ozone hole, have been banished from the refrigerating plant. Chlorinated hydrocarbons, a danger to both man and environment, have long since disappeared from the washing plant for oil-smeared workpieces. However, the alternative water-based processes are not without their disadvantages as soon as large volumes of polluted waste-water are produced. Used in special recycling systems, the cooling lubricants last for around two years; the wash-water for about six months. To gain a better insight into what this means, it is useful to consider a parallel domestic situation in which a ten-liter bucket would be sufficient to catch the waste water accumulating over an entire year from a daily shower using 100 liters of water. Yet, the Mercedes ecologists are interested in more than just reducing the overall quantity of water used. Given the cost and effort necessary for its purification, they also want to minimize the proportion of drinking-quality water used. "We now obtain about two-thirds of our water from the Neckar river or from springs," says Winter.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Utilizing<br>district heating<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>While this approach is good news for the company's finances, the decision to utilize district heating at Bad Cannstatt and Untert&uuml;rkheim is by no means the most economical solution: For example, block-type thermal power plants would be less expensive. From an ecological point of view, however, it is better to use the energy provided by the utilities for combined heat and power purposes.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Europe`s largest<br>photovoltaic installation<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Moreover, a further 435 kilowatts of energy comes from the roof, where Europe's largest building-based arrangement of photovoltaic cells is busy converting solar energy into electricity. Although uneconomical to operate, this 5000-square-meter solar energy "generator" is providing us with valuable experience of solar electricity generation.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>59 percent heat<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>By extracting the heat from the spent air flowing from the halls and-for the first time ever-from cooling lubricants, heat exchangers are also doing their bit to cut energy bills. The heat removed in this way is subsequently used to preheat fresh air. And the savings are impressive: 59 percent of the entire energy is being retrieved thanks to the optimization of heat circulating systems.<p><TD WIDTH=20><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="24_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="27_1_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
