</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Projects: Dry Swarf</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="28_1_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Dry Swarf</b></font><p><table><tr><td valign=top align=left width=380><a href="../pics/27_5.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/27_5.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif">Wherever metal is drilled, sawn, or milled, it's a case of "double, double, toil and trouble". Liters of a special cooling fluid are required to cool component, tool, and machine-and to rinse the swarf away. Of course, getting rid of the heat and swarf brings other troubles in their stead. The cooling lubricants themselves represent a danger to the environment and contaminate both component and workplace. Vaporized lubricant precipitates everywhere in the production hall, attacking rubber seals, paintwork, and-most importantly-the health of the employees themselves. Thanks to a breakthrough made by Daimler-Benz researchers, however, an answer could now be at hand. For the first time, aircraft components are being manufactured using an effectively "dry" process in Dasa's Augsburg plant. Instead of the usual 3000 liters of conventional cooling lubricant, the components now require just 20 thousandths of a liter (ml) per hour. And it is not simply a question of the volume-the new process uses a special oil called FD 1-30 which is completely non-toxic. So much so, in fact, that it could even be eaten. The swarf produced by this process no longer swims in a brew of rinsing fluid, but is effectively dry, with just 0.01 millionth of a liter clinging to every fragment. Metallurgical recycling of the swarf is thus possible without any further cleaning. A few other tricks are also necessary in addition to the super-oil: differently-shaped tools, diamond or other ultrahard, heat-conductive coatings, and a vacuum swarf collection system all play their part in the new process.</table><p><br><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="27_5_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="28_1_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
