<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Projects: The Trick with the Cylinders</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="28_2_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>The Trick with the Cylinders</b></font><p><table><tr><td valign=top align=left width=400><a href="../pics/28_1.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/28_1.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif">"Common rail" may sound like "Railroads for the masses"-and it certainly is revolutionary-but it actually refers to a completely new injection system for diesel engines. In the past, not only did the injection pump have to generate the injection pressure separately for each cylinder using a cam, it also had to repeat the process from scratch for every working cycle. What's more, the injection timing depended on the cam setting. <p>The common-rail system handles the job rather differently. It makes use of a single high-pressure pump, which provides a constant high pressure for all cylinders. The real trick, however, is to be found in the common fuel line-the common rail-where around 30 cubic centimeters of fuel are compressed at a pressure of up to 1350 bar. The individual cylinders are then served by lines branching to the injection nozzles.<p>The pressure in the common rail can be adjusted to any engine speed and load. Sensors measure camshaft and crankshaft speeds, as well as the pressure in the rail, and then pass on this data to the control unit. Finally, a pressure control valve sets the precise pressure in the rail. The optimal relationship between engine speed, load, and pressure has been determined and programmed into the control unit by the engine developers in the course of comprehensive experimental engine studies.<p>At the heart of the system are the injection nozzles. Here, a magnetic valve, which can open and close the nozzle in fractions of a millisecond, allows extremely precise control of both the quantity to be injected and when the process should begin-even at the high pressures used. Unlike conventional injection systems, which require a high r.p.m. to achieve high injection pressures, the common rail manages such a feat at low revolutions. The fast closing time of the magnetic valves also allows a pilot-injection process, whereby the nozzle opens briefly and a minute quantity of fuel-smaller than a pinhead in volume-is injected into the combustion chamber immediately before the main fuel injection. This technique results in a softer start to the main injection and reduces the noise level of a direct-injection engine to that of a prechamber engine. It also limits the temperature rise during combustion, thereby reducing the amount of polluting nitrogen oxides produced.<p>Karl-Heinz Hoffmann, Common Rail Project Director at Mercedes-Benz is enthusiastic about the consequences: "High injection pressure means small injected droplets of fuel which, in turn, results in better combustion of the fuel-air mixture."</table><p><br><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="28_1_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="28_2_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
