<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental-Report `96 - Projects: Dreams of the Natural Car</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="29_1_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Dreams of the Natural Car</b></font><p><table><td align=middle><a href="../pics/28_2.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/28_2.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif"></table><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>Cars made from renewable natural materials may belong to the future, but Mercedes-Benz researchers in Germany and Brazil continue to come up with new uses for natural materials.  <TD width=20><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>Natural rubber, animal hair, and natural fibers from flax, sisal, ramie, coconut, and cotton are all being put to good use in upholstery, door panels, and rear shelves.<tr><td><br></TABLE><p><TABLE border=0><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>From glass fibers<br>to natural fibers<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>But that's not the end of the story by a long way," explains Wolfgang Wittig, head of Plastics and Elastomers at Mercedes-Benz. "Our next project is to replace traditional glass fiber with natural fiber reinforcement." No small undertaking, indeed: with its immense resistance to tearing, glass fiber has long proved practically irreplaceable in automobile construction.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Better and cheaper <br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Further problems dog the rapid extension of natural products to other areas of automobile manufacture. Not only are natural materials usually temperature-sensitive, they tend to retain water and often exhibit extreme variation in quality.<p>Finally, automobile industry specifications are extremely stringent: "The ecological car still has to satisfy standard criteria with regard to safety, reliability, comfort, and performance," emphasizes Dr. J&uuml;rgen G&uuml;nter from the Mercedes-Benz plant in Sindelfingen. His Brazilian colleague Ferdinand Panik agrees: "We can't get carried away with ecological wish fulfillment. Any natural material must be cheaper and, if possible, better than the material it is replacing."<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110> <B>Great advantages<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>However, the 2000 natural materials from which man has extracted, spun, and woven fibers also have qualities which make them attractive for the engineer. And this is true, despite high-technology competition from steel and plastics. Natural materials not only represent a potential new source of income for farmers, they are also good humidity regulators, insulate against heat and noise, and are renewable. Both biodegradable and usually comparatively cheap, they rarely present a health risk, and although normally light they are extremely strong for their weight.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Ramie takes off<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Ramie-a 2.5-meter high Chinese relation of the common stinging nettle and more correctly known as Boehmeria nivea-yields fibers which are practically as tearproof as those made from glass. Developers in Bremen are currently testing ramie as a possible replacement to be used for the interior fittings of the Airbus. The fiber already satisfies one vital requirement for aircraft construction-it is fireproof. Happily, the problem of finding someone expert enough to process the material was also solved when the Bremen team managed to locate a cheesecloth manufacturer in Switzerland. Flax, too, is not only able to withstand almost the same tensile force as ramie, but even out-performs glass fiber on a weight-for-weight basis.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Fiber in plastic<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>Research interest is also focused on plastic-impregnated matting made from natural materials. Although this mixture of nature and chemistry represents a compromise, anything which increases the proportion of the former is welcome. However, this is by no means as straightforward as one might think. For one thing, natural fibers are not particularly resistant to heat and at about 230&#176;-extremely hot for your average plant-the game is generally up. Just two options are therefore left when it comes to embedding the fibers in plastic: either to use a "thermosetting" plastic such as polyurethane which can be processed at low temperatures but is not as strong as one might wish; or to take a thermoplastic polymer such as polypropylene and circumvent the classical processing procedures it normally requires. Here, an extrusion compression molding technique developed by Daimler-Benz researchers at Ulm has contributed to taking some of the heat out of the process, though it still requires further optimization.<p><tr><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=110><B>Fiber in natural matrix<br></B><TD WIDTH=5><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=360>"The dream ecological partnership would be a natural fiber in a genuinely biological matrix," says Thomas F&ouml;lster from Daimler-Benz Research. Natural starch or resin would be ideal fillers which, combined with individual fibers, would allow load-bearing sheets to be molded. The fiber-reinforced natural polymer car would then be truly biodegradable. However, it will take a few more harvests yet, before cars really do "grow on trees."<p><tr><td><br></table><p><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="28_2_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="29_1_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
