<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Projects</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="29_2_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Watch the Birdie</b></font><p><TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=275 valign=top>The first flying machines were based on birds. Before long, however, the early pioneers of flight realized that a plane with flapping wings was no better than<br><TD width=20><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=275 valign=top>a dead duck-it was only with the development of the rigid wing that air travel really took off. But today engineers are taking a another look at those first images from nature. <tr><td><br></TABLE><p><table><tr><td valign=top align=left width=380><a href="../pics/29_1.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=100 border=0 src="../pics/29_1.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=100 src="../../icons/abstand.gif">In order to come up with a more streamlined and thriftier aircraft, scientists at Daimler-Benz Aerospace Airbus in Bremen have begun in part to put the rigid wing concept behind them. Once the wings are given a variable camber, they behave just like those of a bird. This so-called adaptive wing can now adjust to pressure and flow variations not only during takeoff and landing, but at any time during flight. Processing the data received from dozens of tiny sensors, a computer then calculates the optimal wing flap position, offsets this against speed, altitude, and weight, and finally transmits the resulting adjustment to the wing flap motors.With the help of adaptive wing technology plus another few tricks, scientists hope to reduce fuel consumption for future Airbus aircraft by around 15 percent-an enormous amount when one considers that consumption has already been halved since the birth of the first Airbus model, the A300, back in 1972. In line with this offensive, "RaWid"-the German acronym for a project to reduce aerodynamic drag-was launched last year. The project is being jointly financed by Daimler-Benz and the German government, with each partner providing funds in the region of DM 20 million.According to project leader Dr. Joseph Mertens, the target savings here might well even be bettered: "Once technological improvements bring about a 15 percent drop in resistance, the environmental results begin to snowball." For example, less drag means less fuel consumption, which in turn means less weight of fuel to be transported which itself results in less fuel consumption. According to Mertens, "realistic estimates suggest a drop in fuel consumption of around 25 percent per passenger kilometer."Long-term perspectives even go so far as to offer the prospect of a 36 percent reduction in drag by 2015, with the lion's share of the savings coming from the application of laminar technology to the wing, tail, nacelles, and fuselage. One of the key ideas currently being scrutinized by the experts is the introduction of self-cleaning wings. Given that even the tiniest particle of dirt can radically affect the smoothness of the wing surface, thereby causing turbulence, the advantage of such an arrangement is obvious.In addition to adjustable wing flaps, movable contouring or "bulges" on the wings should help perfect the adaptive wing. According to the designers, this controllable cambering should weaken the effect of a so-called compression wave-a sudden build up of pressure on the wing. The source of an unwanted increase in drag, this type of wave arises when the air flowing over the wing of a jet flying subsonically is accelerated to a supersonic velocity. </table><p><br><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="29_1_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="29_2_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
