<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Projects: No NOxious Gases</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="30_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>No NOxious Gases</b></font><p><table><tr><td valign=top align=left width=380><a href="../pics/29_2.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=80 border=0 src="../pics/29_2.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=80 src="../../icons/abstand.gif">The list of sins chalked up by the various oxides of nitrogen makes for sorry reading. Up to 60 percent of these air pollutants originate in vehicle exhaust and they are held responsible for our dying forests, summer smog, high ozone levels, and acid rain.<br>A catalytic converter removes around 90 percent of the nitrogen oxides produced by conventional SI engines, but does not work with diesel and lean-burn SI engines-i.e., those running on excess oxygen. Fortunately, Daimler-Benz scientists have devised an alternative solution. The fruit of two projects-"Low-Emission Diesel Motor" and "Post-Engine Purification"-the new method involves installing absorbers in the exhaust system which retain the nitrogen oxides in the exhaust gases. When the absorbers are full, the nitrogen oxides are desorbed and added to the engine intake air. Once in the combustion chamber the pollutants are reduced to harmless substances such as elemental nitrogen.Officially, the method is known as "Selective NOx Recycling with Inner-Engine Non-Catalytic NOx Reduction" or "SNR" for short. Preliminary tests with a diesel engine have been very promising. Without special optimization, nitrogen oxide emission was already down by 50 percent. An environmental success, the process also functions perfectly both at low exhaust gas temperatures and for engines which permanently run on excess oxygen. Finally, it functions without any additional reducing agent.</table><p><br><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="29_2_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../projek_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Projects</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="30_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search/I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
