<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Report `96 - Highlights: Keeping Tabs on Exhaust and Waste</TITLE></HEAD><BODY background="../../icons/db_back1.jpg" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#2060A0" VLINK="#606060" ALINK="#E0E0FF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="../../index_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=33 SRC="../../icons/db_home.gif"></A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/envirokl.gif"></A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_up.gif"></A><A HREF="12_2_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/menu_rig.gif"></A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/db_such.gif"></A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/mailkl.gif"></A> <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 WIDTH=54 HEIGHT=44 SRC="../../icons/helpkl.gif"></A><BR><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><font size=+2><b>Keeping Tabs on Exhaust and Waste</b></font><p><table><tr><td valign=top align=left width=380><a href="../pics/12_1.jpg"><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=100 height=125 border=0 src="../pics/12_1.gif"></a><img align=left vspace=3 hspace=-2 width=6 height=125 src="../../icons/abstand.gif">Measurement networks are a key feature of environmental protection. Constant analysis is vital if harmful emissions are to be avoided and the success of protection measures confirmed. Since the end of 1995, the Mercedes-Benz plants at Mettingen and Untert&uuml;rkheim have been operating a pilot measurement network which continually monitors all of the relevant exhaust air and waste-water outlets. Initially, the network will run continuously for a three year test phase. 39 exhaust chimneys, two waste-water outlets, and two weather stations measure a total of 58 different parameters including dust, nitrogen oxides, and carbon monoxide-24 hours a day. The results are fed continuously to a central computer, where they are evaluated and stored. In the event of an irregularity, the personnel responsible are automatically notified by radio. This constant flow of measurement data provides an ideal basis upon which decisions can be made to guarantee the protection of the surrounding environment. But the pilot project encompasses much more than merely observing the stipulated emissions regulations. It also offers a chance to optimize the exhaust air treatment facilities and to use trend analyses, for example, to determine the optimal maintenance and repair dates.</table><p><br><IMG WIDTH=592 HEIGHT=16 SRC="../../lines/db_592.gif"><P><TABLE><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=550><H5><A HREF="12_1_g.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Deutsch</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../index_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Home</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../envir_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environment</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../ub96_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Environmental Report '96</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../schlag_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Highlights</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="12_2_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Next</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../search/search_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Search</I>&nbsp;]</A><A HREF="../../mail/mail_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Dialog</I>&nbsp;]</A>   <A HREF="../../help/help_e.htm">[&nbsp;<I>Help</I>&nbsp;]</A></H5></TABLE><ADDRESS>&copy; Daimler-Benz, last update: 08/06/1996</ADDRESS><P></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
